raftPicks}}\n{{Philadelphia Eagles roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hurts, Jalen}}\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Harris County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Texas]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide football players]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma Sooners football players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Eagles players]]\n", "name_user": "Bender235", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jalen_Hurts"}
{"title_page": "2010 Pinstripe Bowl", "text_new": "{{Infobox NCAA football yearly game\n| Game Name          = Pinstripe Bowl\n| Optional Subheader = Inaugural Pinstripe Bowl\n| Title Sponsor      = [[New Era Cap Company|New Era]]\n| Image              = [[File:Pinstripe logo.png]]\n| Caption            = \n| Date Game Played   = December 30\n| Year Game Played   = 2010\n| Football Season    = 2010\n| Stadium            = [[Yankee Stadium]]\n| City               = [[Bronx, New York]]\n| Visitor School        = [[Kansas State University]]\n| Visitor Name Short    = Kansas State \n| Visitor Nickname      = Wildcats\n| Visitor Record        = 7\u20135 <!-- Field should contain record prior to game -->\n| Visitor AP            =\n| Visitor Coaches       =\n| Visitor BCS           =\n| Visitor Coach         = [[Bill Snyder]]\n| Visitor Conference    = [[Big 12 Conference|Big 12]]\n| Visitor1           = 7\n| Visitor2           = 7\n| Visitor3           = 7\n| Visitor4           = 13\n| Home School     = Syracuse University\n| Home Name Short = Syracuse \n| Home Nickname   = Orange\n| Home Record     = 7\u20135 <!-- Field should contain record prior to game -->\n| Home AP         =\n| Home Coaches    = \n| Home BCS        =\n| Home Coach      = [[Doug Marrone]]\n| Home Conference = [[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East]]\n| Home1              = 7\n| Home2              = 7\n| Home3              = 13\n| Home4              = 9\n| MVP                = \n| Anthem             =\n| Odds               = Even <ref>''Vegas Insider'', December 24, 2010</ref> \n| Referee            = \n| Halftime           =\n| Attendance         = 38,274 \n| Payout             = 2,000,000 per team\n| US Network         = [[ESPN]]\n| US Announcers      = [[Bob Wischusen]] and [[Brian Griese]]\n| Ratings            = 2.26\n| Intl Network       =\n| Intl Announcers    =\n| FirstGameEverPlayed=yes\n}}\n\nThe '''2010 New Era Pinstripe Bowl'''  was the first edition of this [[college football]] [[bowl game]], and was played at [[Yankee Stadium]] in [[Bronx, New York]].  The game started at 3:20 p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|ET]] on December 30, [[2010 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2010]], and was telecast on [[ESPN]].  The game featured the [[2010 Syracuse Orange football team|Syracuse Orange]] of the [[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East Conference]] and the [[2010 Kansas State Wildcats football team|Kansas State Wildcats]] of the [[Big 12 Conference]]. [[New Era Cap Company]] was the title sponsor of the game.<ref>Richard Sandomir, [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/10/sports/ncaafootball/10sandomir.html It\u2019s New York. It\u2019s the Stadium. It\u2019s the Pinstripe Bowl], ''The New York Times'', March 9, 2010</ref> It ended with Syracuse defeating Kansas State, 36-34.\n\nThe game was played four days after [[December 2010 North American blizzard|one of the worst blizzards in New York City history]], affecting travel for the teams and their fans.\n\n== Teams ==\n===Kansas State Wildcats===\n{{see also|2010 Kansas State Wildcats football team}}\nKansas State officially accepted an invitation to the bowl on December 3, 2010, after completing a 7-5 regular season.<ref>https://www.wsj.com/articles/AP6de67e8faf2c4b3b9440612f6bdd57b5</ref>  The bowl marked the Wildcats return to post-season for the first time since 2006.  It was the 14th bowl game in school history for K-State.  Coach Bill Snyder coached the Wildcats in all but two of their previous bowls.\n\n===Syracuse Orange===\n{{see also|2010 Syracuse Orange football team}}\n\nSyracuse officially accepted an invitation to the bowl on December 3, 2010.<ref>http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=5875702</ref>  Second year head coach [[Doug Marrone]], who grew up in the Bronx, just minutes from the old Yankee Stadium led the Orange to a 7-5 record and their first bowl game since the [[2004 Champs Sports Bowl]].  Syracuse was required to win seven games in order to become bowl-eligible as two of their victories came over [[Football Championship Subdivision]] opponents.  Only one of the victories is allowed to count toward bowl eligibility.\n\n==Game summary==\n===Scoring===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Scoring Play\n! Score\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''1st Quarter'''\n|-\n|KSU - [[Daniel Thomas (running back)|Daniel Thomas]] 51-yard run (Josh Cherry kick), 14:32 \n|KSU 7-0\n|-\n|SYR - [[Ryan Nassib]] 52-yard pass to Marcus Sales ([[Ross Krautman]] kick), 3:16\n|TIE 7-7\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''2nd Quarter'''\n|-\n|SYR - Ryan Nassib 36-yard pass to Marcus Sales (Ross Krautman kick), 9:35\n|SYR 14-7\n|-\n|KSU - Daniel Thomas 10-yard run (Josh Cherry kick), 1:51 \n|TIE 14-14\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''3rd Quarter'''\n|-\n|SYR - Delone Carter 7-yard run (Ross Krautman kick), 12:11\n|SYR 21-14\n|-\n|KSU - [[Carson Coffman]] 10-yard pass to Chris Harper (Josh Cherry kick), 6:34 \n|TIE 21-21\n|-\n|SYR - Delone Carter 15-yard run (Ross Krautman kick missed), 2:11\n|SYR 27-21\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''4th Quarter'''\n|-\n|KSU - Daniel Thomas 1-yard run (Josh Cherry kick), 11:03 \n|KSU 28-27\n|-\n|SYR - Ryan Nassib 44-yard pass to Marcus Sales (Two-point conversion failed), 7:53\n|SYR 33-28\n|-\n|SYR - Ross Krautman 39-yard field goal, 3:08\n|SYR 36-28\n|-\n|KSU - Carson Coffman 30-yard pass to Adrian Hilburn  (Two-Point Conversion Failed), 1:13\n|SYR 36-34\n|}\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Statistics  !! Kansas St. !! Syracuse\n|-\n| First Downs || 19 || 23\n|-\n| Total offense, plays-yards || 61-379 || 65-498\n|-\n|Rushes-yards (net)|| 121 || 259\n|-\n|Passes, Comp-Att-Yds || 18-25-258 || 13-22-239\n|-\n|Fumbles-Interceptions|| 0-0 || 1-0\n|-\n| Time of Possession|| 31:38 || 28:22\n|}\n\n==The Bronx Salute==\n===The call===\nWith 1:13 left in the game, Kansas State's [[Adrian Hilburn]] scored a 30-yard touchdown to pull KSU within two points of a tie.  Following the score, Hilburn made a military hand [[salute]] toward the crowd and was penalized for unsportsmanlike conduct.  Because of the 15-yard penalty, Kansas State had to attempt a [[two-point conversion]] from the 17-yard line.<ref name=\"lubbock\" />  The conversion failed, accounting for the margin in the final score.  The call was considered highly controversial, and according to ESPN determined the outcome of the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/new-york/ncf/news/story?id=5972281|publisher=[[ESPN]]|title=Adrian Hilburn 'devastated' by call|accessdate=January 1, 2013|date=December 31, 2010|first=Kieran|last=Darcy}}</ref>\n\n===Aftermath===\nDue to the impact from this call, the NCAA chose in the next year's rule changes to not penalize celebrating in general but to penalize only taunting.<ref name=\"lubbock\">{{cite web|url=http://lubbockonline.com/interact/blog-post/david-just/2011-07-25/kansas-state-salute-penalty-prompts-rule-change#.UOOo2XfNmSo|title=Kansas State salute penalty prompts rule change|first=David|last=Just|accessdate=January 1, 2013|date=July 11, 2011|publisher=[[Lubbock Avalanche-Journal]]}}</ref>  The call was called \"one of the most infamous plays of the college football season in 2010\" and was given the name \"The Bronx Salute.\"  It later was used as an example of incorrect interpretation of the new celebration rules.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/ncfnation/tag/_/name/adrian-hilburn|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=July 27, 2011|title=Snyder weighs in on rules change|accessdate=January 1, 2013|first=David|last=Ubben}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n* This was the first bowl game played in New York since the 1962 [[Gotham Bowl]] (at [[old Yankee Stadium]]), where 6,166 fans saw [[1962 Nebraska Cornhuskers football team|Nebraska]] defeat [[1962 Miami Hurricanes football team|Miami]] 36-34 on frozen turf.\n* Syracuse and Kansas State met twice before in school history.  All of their matchups have come in bowl games.  K-State defeated the Orange in the 1997 [[Fiesta Bowl]], 35-18 and the Orange were victorious by a score of 26-3 in the [[2001 Insight.com Bowl]]. This was their first meeting outside the [[Phoenix Metropolitan Area]].\n*Senior Andrew Lewis and freshman Brice Hawkes were suspended for a rules violation by Syracuse head coach Doug Marrone.{{Citation needed|date=December 2010}}\n* The final result of the 2010 Pinstripe Bowl was subject to criticism due to an \"Excessive Celebration\" [[Penalty (American football)|Penalty]] against Kansas State (see section above: ''The Bronx Salute'').<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://college-football.blogs.cbssports.com/mcc/blogs/entry/24156338/26739717 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-04-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813203652/http://college-football.blogs.cbssports.com/mcc/blogs/entry/24156338/26739717 |archive-date=2011-08-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.espn.com/college-football/boxscore?gameId=303640183 Box score] at [[ESPN]]\n\n{{2010 bowl game navbox}}\n{{Pinstripe Bowl navbox}}\n{{Kansas State Wildcats bowl game navbox}}\n{{Syracuse Orange bowl game navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pinstripe Bowl, 2010}}\n[[Category:2010\u201311 NCAA football bowl games]]\n[[Category:Pinstripe Bowl|2010]]\n[[Category:Kansas State Wildcats football bowl games|2010]]\n[[Category:Syracuse Orange football bowl games|2010]]\n[[Category:December 2010 sports events in the United States]]\n[[Category:2010 in sports in New York City]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NCAA football yearly game\n| Game Name          = Pinstripe Bowl\n| Optional Subheader = Inaugural Pinstripe Bowl\n| Title Sponsor      = [[New Era Cap Company|New Era]]\n| Image              = [[File:Pinstripe logo.png]]\n| Caption            = \n| Date Game Played   = December 30\n| Year Game Played   = 2010\n| Football Season    = 2010\n| Stadium            = [[Yankee Stadium]]\n| City               = [[Bronx, New York]]\n| Visitor School        = [[Kansas State University]]\n| Visitor Name Short    = Kansas State \n| Visitor Nickname      = Wildcats\n| Visitor Record        = 7\u20135 <!-- Field should contain record prior to game -->\n| Visitor AP            =\n| Visitor Coaches       =\n| Visitor BCS           =\n| Visitor Coach         = [[Bill Snyder]]\n| Visitor Conference    = [[Big 12 Conference|Big 12]]\n| Visitor1           = 7\n| Visitor2           = 7\n| Visitor3           = 7\n| Visitor4           = 13\n| Home School     = Syracuse University\n| Home Name Short = Syracuse \n| Home Nickname   = Orange\n| Home Record     = 7\u20135 <!-- Field should contain record prior to game -->\n| Home AP         =\n| Home Coaches    = \n| Home BCS        =\n| Home Coach      = [[Doug Marrone]]\n| Home Conference = [[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East]]\n| Home1              = 7\n| Home2              = 7\n| Home3              = 13\n| Home4              = 9\n| MVP                = \n| Anthem             =\n| Odds               = Even <ref>''Vegas Insider'', December 24, 2010</ref> \n| Referee            = \n| Halftime           =\n| Attendance         = 38,274 \n| Payout             = 2,000,000 per team\n| US Network         = [[ESPN]]\n| US Announcers      = [[Bob Wischusen]] and [[Brian Griese]]\n| Ratings            = 2.26\n| Intl Network       =\n| Intl Announcers    =\n| FirstGameEverPlayed=yes\n}}\n\nThe '''2010 New Era Pinstripe Bowl'''  was the first edition of this [[college football]] [[bowl game]], and was played at [[Yankee Stadium]] in [[Bronx, New York]].  The game started at 3:20 p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|ET]] on December 30, [[2010 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2010]], and was telecast on [[ESPN]].  The game featured the [[2010 Syracuse Orange football team|Syracuse Orange]] of the [[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East Conference]] and the [[2010 Kansas State Wildcats football team|Kansas State Wildcats]] of the [[Big 12 Conference]]. [[New Era Cap Company]] was the title sponsor of the game.<ref>Richard Sandomir, [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/10/sports/ncaafootball/10sandomir.html It\u2019s New York. It\u2019s the Stadium. It\u2019s the Pinstripe Bowl], ''The New York Times'', March 9, 2010</ref> It ended with Syracuse defeating Kansas State, 36-34.\n\nThe game was played four days after [[December 2010 North American blizzard|one of the worst blizzards in New York City history]], affecting travel for the teams and their fans.\n\n== Teams ==\n===Kansas State Wildcats===\n{{see also|2010 Kansas State Wildcats football team}}\nKansas State officially accepted an invitation to the bowl on December 3, 2010, after completing a 7-5 regular season.<ref>https://www.wsj.com/articles/AP6de67e8faf2c4b3b9440612f6bdd57b5</ref>  The bowl marked the Wildcats return to post-season for the first time since 2006.  It was the 14th bowl game in school history for K-State.  Coach Bill Snyder coached the Wildcats in all but two of their previous bowls.\n\n===Syracuse Orange===\n{{see also|2010 Syracuse Orange football team}}\n\nSyracuse officially accepted an invitation to the bowl on December 3, 2010.<ref>http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=5875702</ref>  Second year head coach [[Doug Marrone]], who grew up in the Bronx, just minutes from the old Yankee Stadium led the Orange to a 7-5 record and their first bowl game since the [[2004 Champs Sports Bowl]].  Syracuse was required to win seven games in order to become bowl-eligible as two of their victories came over [[Football Championship Subdivision]] opponents.  Only one of the victories is allowed to count toward bowl eligibility.\n\n==Game summary==\n===Scoring===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Scoring Play\n! Score\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''1st Quarter'''\n|-\n|KSU - [[Daniel Thomas (American football)|Daniel Thomas]] 51-yard run (Josh Cherry kick), 14:32 \n|KSU 7-0\n|-\n|SYR - [[Ryan Nassib]] 52-yard pass to Marcus Sales ([[Ross Krautman]] kick), 3:16\n|TIE 7-7\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''2nd Quarter'''\n|-\n|SYR - Ryan Nassib 36-yard pass to Marcus Sales (Ross Krautman kick), 9:35\n|SYR 14-7\n|-\n|KSU - Daniel Thomas 10-yard run (Josh Cherry kick), 1:51 \n|TIE 14-14\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''3rd Quarter'''\n|-\n|SYR - Delone Carter 7-yard run (Ross Krautman kick), 12:11\n|SYR 21-14\n|-\n|KSU - [[Carson Coffman]] 10-yard pass to Chris Harper (Josh Cherry kick), 6:34 \n|TIE 21-21\n|-\n|SYR - Delone Carter 15-yard run (Ross Krautman kick missed), 2:11\n|SYR 27-21\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''4th Quarter'''\n|-\n|KSU - Daniel Thomas 1-yard run (Josh Cherry kick), 11:03 \n|KSU 28-27\n|-\n|SYR - Ryan Nassib 44-yard pass to Marcus Sales (Two-point conversion failed), 7:53\n|SYR 33-28\n|-\n|SYR - Ross Krautman 39-yard field goal, 3:08\n|SYR 36-28\n|-\n|KSU - Carson Coffman 30-yard pass to Adrian Hilburn  (Two-Point Conversion Failed), 1:13\n|SYR 36-34\n|}\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Statistics  !! Kansas St. !! Syracuse\n|-\n| First Downs || 19 || 23\n|-\n| Total offense, plays-yards || 61-379 || 65-498\n|-\n|Rushes-yards (net)|| 121 || 259\n|-\n|Passes, Comp-Att-Yds || 18-25-258 || 13-22-239\n|-\n|Fumbles-Interceptions|| 0-0 || 1-0\n|-\n| Time of Possession|| 31:38 || 28:22\n|}\n\n==The Bronx Salute==\n===The call===\nWith 1:13 left in the game, Kansas State's [[Adrian Hilburn]] scored a 30-yard touchdown to pull KSU within two points of a tie.  Following the score, Hilburn made a military hand [[salute]] toward the crowd and was penalized for unsportsmanlike conduct.  Because of the 15-yard penalty, Kansas State had to attempt a [[two-point conversion]] from the 17-yard line.<ref name=\"lubbock\" />  The conversion failed, accounting for the margin in the final score.  The call was considered highly controversial, and according to ESPN determined the outcome of the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/new-york/ncf/news/story?id=5972281|publisher=[[ESPN]]|title=Adrian Hilburn 'devastated' by call|accessdate=January 1, 2013|date=December 31, 2010|first=Kieran|last=Darcy}}</ref>\n\n===Aftermath===\nDue to the impact from this call, the NCAA chose in the next year's rule changes to not penalize celebrating in general but to penalize only taunting.<ref name=\"lubbock\">{{cite web|url=http://lubbockonline.com/interact/blog-post/david-just/2011-07-25/kansas-state-salute-penalty-prompts-rule-change#.UOOo2XfNmSo|title=Kansas State salute penalty prompts rule change|first=David|last=Just|accessdate=January 1, 2013|date=July 11, 2011|publisher=[[Lubbock Avalanche-Journal]]}}</ref>  The call was called \"one of the most infamous plays of the college football season in 2010\" and was given the name \"The Bronx Salute.\"  It later was used as an example of incorrect interpretation of the new celebration rules.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/ncfnation/tag/_/name/adrian-hilburn|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=July 27, 2011|title=Snyder weighs in on rules change|accessdate=January 1, 2013|first=David|last=Ubben}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n* This was the first bowl game played in New York since the 1962 [[Gotham Bowl]] (at [[old Yankee Stadium]]), where 6,166 fans saw [[1962 Nebraska Cornhuskers football team|Nebraska]] defeat [[1962 Miami Hurricanes football team|Miami]] 36-34 on frozen turf.\n* Syracuse and Kansas State met twice before in school history.  All of their matchups have come in bowl games.  K-State defeated the Orange in the 1997 [[Fiesta Bowl]], 35-18 and the Orange were victorious by a score of 26-3 in the [[2001 Insight.com Bowl]]. This was their first meeting outside the [[Phoenix Metropolitan Area]].\n*Senior Andrew Lewis and freshman Brice Hawkes were suspended for a rules violation by Syracuse head coach Doug Marrone.{{Citation needed|date=December 2010}}\n* The final result of the 2010 Pinstripe Bowl was subject to criticism due to an \"Excessive Celebration\" [[Penalty (American football)|Penalty]] against Kansas State (see section above: ''The Bronx Salute'').<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://college-football.blogs.cbssports.com/mcc/blogs/entry/24156338/26739717 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-04-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813203652/http://college-football.blogs.cbssports.com/mcc/blogs/entry/24156338/26739717 |archive-date=2011-08-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.espn.com/college-football/boxscore?gameId=303640183 Box score] at [[ESPN]]\n\n{{2010 bowl game navbox}}\n{{Pinstripe Bowl navbox}}\n{{Kansas State Wildcats bowl game navbox}}\n{{Syracuse Orange bowl game navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pinstripe Bowl, 2010}}\n[[Category:2010\u201311 NCAA football bowl games]]\n[[Category:Pinstripe Bowl|2010]]\n[[Category:Kansas State Wildcats football bowl games|2010]]\n[[Category:Syracuse Orange football bowl games|2010]]\n[[Category:2010 in sports in New York City]]\n", "name_user": "KingSkyLord", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2010_Pinstripe_Bowl"}
{"title_page": "Miss de V\u00e8re (English Jig)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Miss de V\u00e8re\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| italic title   = no\n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Georges M\u00e9li\u00e8s]]\n| producer       =\n| writer         = \n| narrator       = \n| starring       = Elise de V\u00e8re\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = [[Star Film Company]]\n| released       = 1896\n| runtime        = 20 meters/65 feet<ref name=Hammond>{{cite book|last=Hammond|first=Paul|title=Marvellous M\u00e9li\u00e8s|year=1974|publisher=Gordon Fraser|location=London|isbn=0900406380|page=135}}</ref>\n| country        = [[France]]\n| language       = [[Silent film|Silent]]\n| budget         = \n| gross          =\n| preceded_by    = \n| followed_by    = \n}}{{italic title|all=yes}}\n[[File:\u00c9lise de V\u00e8re, btv1b85969082-p039, 6.jpg|thumb|\u00c9lise de V\u00e8re]]\n'''''Miss de V\u00e8re (English Jig)''''' ({{lang-fr|Miss de V\u00e8re}}) was an 1896 French [[silent film]] directed by [[Georges M\u00e9li\u00e8s]]. It was released by M\u00e9li\u00e8s's [[Star Film Company]] and is numbered 45 in its catalogues.<ref name=Hammond /> The performer, the \"Miss de V\u00e8re\" of the title, is the dancer and actress [[:fr:Elise de V\u00e8re|Elise de V\u00e8re]].<ref>{{citation|author=[[San Francisco Silent Film Festival]]|title=Flipbook 2 - La danse|work=[[Vimeo]]|date=2020|url=https://vimeo.com/410423777|accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref> She was one of the daughters of Charles de Vere (real name H. S. G. Williams), an Englishman who had worked as a professional magician and who was then the owner of a Paris shop selling conjuror's supplies, electrical equipment, and films.<ref name=Barnes>{{cite book|last=Barnes|first=John|title=Filming the Boer War|year=1992|publisher=Bishopgate Press|location=London|isbn=1852190469|page=69}}</ref>\n\n''Miss de V\u00e8re'' in a complete form is currently presumed [[Lost film|lost]], but a [[flipbook]] produced by L\u00e9on Beaulieu around 1896\u201397, rediscovered in the mid-2010s in a private collection, appears to preserve a fragment of the film.<ref>{{citation|title=L\u00e9on Beaulieu's Pocket Cinematograph|first1=Thierry|last1=Lecointe|first2=Robert|last2=Byrne|publisher=[[San Francisco Silent Film Festival]]|work=silentfilm.org|date=2019|url=https://silentfilm.org/leon-beaulieus-pocket-cinematograph/|accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|0000094}}\n* [https://vimeo.com/410423777 Flipbook] on [[Vimeo]], tentatively identified as a fragment on ''Miss de V\u00e8re'' \n\n{{Georges M\u00e9li\u00e8s}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miss de Vere (English Jig)}}\n[[Category:1896 films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French silent short films]]\n[[Category:French black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Georges M\u00e9li\u00e8s]]\n[[Category:Lost French films]]\n\n\n{{1890s-France-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Miss de V\u00e8re\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| italic title   = no\n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Georges M\u00e9li\u00e8s]]\n| producer       =\n| writer         = \n| narrator       = \n| starring       = Elise de V\u00e8re\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = [[Star Film Company]]\n| released       = 1896\n| runtime        = 20 meters/65 feet<ref name=Hammond>{{cite book|last=Hammond|first=Paul|title=Marvellous M\u00e9li\u00e8s|year=1974|publisher=Gordon Fraser|location=London|isbn=0900406380|page=135}}</ref>\n| country        = [[France]]\n| language       = [[Silent film|Silent]]\n| budget         = \n| gross          =\n| preceded_by    = \n| followed_by    = \n}}{{italic title|all=yes}}\n[[File:\u00c9lise de V\u00e8re, btv1b85969082-p039, 6.jpg|\u00c9lise de V\u00e8re]]\n'''''Miss de V\u00e8re (English Jig)''''' ({{lang-fr|Miss de V\u00e8re}}) was an 1896 French [[silent film]] directed by [[Georges M\u00e9li\u00e8s]]. It was released by M\u00e9li\u00e8s's [[Star Film Company]] and is numbered 45 in its catalogues.<ref name=Hammond /> The performer, the \"Miss de V\u00e8re\" of the title, is the dancer and actress [[:fr:Elise de V\u00e8re|Elise de V\u00e8re]].<ref>{{citation|author=[[San Francisco Silent Film Festival]]|title=Flipbook 2 - La danse|work=[[Vimeo]]|date=2020|url=https://vimeo.com/410423777|accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref> She was one of the daughters of Charles de Vere (real name H. S. G. Williams), an Englishman who had worked as a professional magician and who was then the owner of a Paris shop selling conjuror's supplies, electrical equipment, and films.<ref name=Barnes>{{cite book|last=Barnes|first=John|title=Filming the Boer War|year=1992|publisher=Bishopgate Press|location=London|isbn=1852190469|page=69}}</ref>\n\n''Miss de V\u00e8re'' in a complete form is currently presumed [[Lost film|lost]], but a [[flipbook]] produced by L\u00e9on Beaulieu around 1896\u201397, rediscovered in the mid-2010s in a private collection, appears to preserve a fragment of the film.<ref>{{citation|title=L\u00e9on Beaulieu's Pocket Cinematograph|first1=Thierry|last1=Lecointe|first2=Robert|last2=Byrne|publisher=[[San Francisco Silent Film Festival]]|work=silentfilm.org|date=2019|url=https://silentfilm.org/leon-beaulieus-pocket-cinematograph/|accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|0000094}}\n* [https://vimeo.com/410423777 Flipbook] on [[Vimeo]], tentatively identified as a fragment on ''Miss de V\u00e8re'' \n\n{{Georges M\u00e9li\u00e8s}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miss de Vere (English Jig)}}\n[[Category:1896 films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French silent short films]]\n[[Category:French black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Georges M\u00e9li\u00e8s]]\n[[Category:Lost French films]]\n\n\n{{1890s-France-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lemuellio", "label": "safe", "comment": "format", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miss_de_V%C3%A8re_(English_Jig)"}
