s?com=institucional&name=pubFile77&downloadname=D%3A%5Cpromedios%20met%5CPromedios%2071-00.xls |title=Promedios 71-00 |publisher=IDEAM |language=Spanish |accessdate=18 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017083756/http://institucional.ideam.gov.co/descargas?com=institucional&name=pubFile77&downloadname=D%3A%5Cpromedios%20met%5CPromedios%2071-00.xls |archive-date=17 October 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n}}\n\n=== Urban layout and nomenclature ===\n[[File:How-Bogota-Streets-are-Numbered-and-Named.png|thumb|Street arrangement of Bogot\u00e1 based on the Cartesian coordinate system: North is to the right]]\n[[File:Bogota as seen from Montserrat.jpg|thumb|View of Bogota from the mountain Monserrate]]\n\nBogot\u00e1 has 20 localities, or districts, forming an extensive network of neighborhoods. Areas of higher economic status tend to be located in the north, close to the Eastern Hills in the districts of [[Chapinero]], [[Usaqu\u00e9n]] and the east of [[Suba, Bogot\u00e1|Suba]]. The lower middle class inhabit the central, western and northwestern parts of the city.{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}. The working-class neighborhoods are located in the south, some of them [[Shanty towns|squatter areas]].{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nThe urban layout in the center of the city is based on the focal point of a square or plaza, typical of Spanish-founded settlements, but the layout gradually becomes more modern in outlying neighborhoods. The types of roads are classified as ''Calles'' (streets), which run from west to east horizontally, with street numbers increasing towards the north, and also towards the south (with the suffix \"Sur\") from Calle 0 down south. ''Carreras'' (roads) run from north to south vertically, with numbering increasing from east to west. (with the suffix \"Este\" for roads east of Carrera 0). At the southeast of the city, the addresses are logically ''sur-este''. Other types of roads more common in newer parts of the city may be termed ''Eje'' (Axis), ''Diagonal'' or ''Transversal''.\nThe numbering system for street addresses recently changed, and numbers are assigned according to street rank from main avenues to smaller avenues and local streets. Some of Bogot\u00e1's main roads, which also go by a proper name in addition to a number, are:\n* Norte-Quito-Sur or NQS (North Quito South Avenue, from 9th Rd at north following railway to 30th Rd, or Quito City Avenue, and Southern Highway)\n* Autopista Norte-Avenida Caracas (Northern Highway, or 45th Rd, joined to Caracas Avenue, or 14th Rd)\n* Avenida Circunvalar (or 1st Rd)\n* Avenida Suba (60th transversal from 100th St the Suba Hills; 145th St from Suba Hills westward)\n* Avenida El Dorado (El Dorado Avenue, or 26th St)\n* Avenida de las Am\u00e9ricas (Avenue of the Americas, from 34th street at east to 6th street at west)\n* Avenida Primero de Mayo (May First Avenue, or 22nd St South)\n* Avenida Ciudad de Cali (Cali City Avenue, or 86th Rd)\n* Avenida Boyac\u00e1 (Boyac\u00e1 Avenue, or 72nd Rd)\n* Autopista Sur (Southern Highway)\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Localities (districts) ===\n{{Bogota DC}}\n\n=== Surrounding towns ===\n{{Geographic location\n|Center    = Bogot\u00e1, [[Capital districts and territories|Capital District]]\n|North     = [[Ch\u00eda, Cundinamarca|Ch\u00eda]]\n|Northeast = [[La Calera, Colombia|La Calera]]\n|East      = [[Choach\u00ed]]\n|Southeast = [[Chipaque]]\n|South     = [[Soacha]]\n|Southwest = [[San Antonio del Tequendama|Tequendama]]\n|West      = [[Mosquera, Cundinamarca|Mosquera]]\n|Northwest = [[Cota, Cundinamarca|Cota]]\n|image     =\n}}\n\n== Demographics ==\n{| class=\"wikitable floatleft\"\n|-\n| Population of Bogot\u00e1 by year\n|-\n| {{Graph:Population history|Q2841}}\n|-\n|}\n{{Historical Populations\n|type =\n|percentages=pagr\n|footnote = <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dane.gov.co/files/censo2005/PERFIL_PDF_CG2005/11001T7T000.PDF |title=Microsoft Word - PerfilMunicipal.doc |accessdate=2013-03-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403010130/http://www.dane.gov.co/files/censo2005/PERFIL_PDF_CG2005/11001T7T000.PDF |archive-date=3 April 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dane.gov.co/files/censo2018/proyecciones-de-poblacion/Proyecciones_de_Poblacion_2018-2020.xls |title=Projections|date=2018 |website=www.dane.gov.co |format=PDF|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n|1775|16233\n|1800|21964\n|1832|28341\n|1870|40883\n|1912|121257\n|1918|143994\n|1928|235702\n|1938|325650\n|1951|715250\n|1964|1697311\n|1973|2855065\n|1985|4236490\n|1993|5484244\n|2005|6778691\n|2018|7412566\n|2020|7743955\n}}\nThe largest and most populous city in Colombia, Bogot\u00e1 had 7,412,566 inhabitants within the city's limits (2018 census),<ref name=\"auto\"/> with a population density of approximately 4,310 inhabitants per square kilometer. Only 25,166 people are located in rural areas of Capital District. 47.8% of the population are male and 52.2% women.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n[[File:Bogot\u00e1 Future Population (Medium Variant).png|thumb|Bogot\u00e1 Future Population (Medium Variant)]]\n\nIn Bogot\u00e1, as in the rest of the country, urbanization has accelerated due to industrialization as well as complex political and social reasons such as poverty and violence, which led to migration from rural to urban areas throughout the twentieth and twenty-first centuries.{{Citation needed|date=October 2015}} A dramatic example of this is the number of displaced people who have arrived in Bogot\u00e1 due to the internal armed conflict.{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nSome estimates show that Bogot\u00e1's [[floating population]] may be as high as 4 million people, most of them being migrant workers from other departments and displaced people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dane.gov.co/|title=Departamento Administrativo Nacional de Estad\u00edstica (DANE)|work=dane.gov.co|access-date=10 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110227230340/http://www.dane.gov.co/|archive-date=27 February 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> The majority of the displaced population lives in the [[Ciudad Bol\u00edvar (Bogot\u00e1)|Ciudad Bol\u00edvar]], [[Kennedy (Bogot\u00e1)|Kennedy]], [[Usme]], and [[Bosa (Bogot\u00e1)|Bosa]] sections.{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n===Ethnic Groups===\n{{main|Race and ethnicity in Bogot\u00e1|l1=Human biological diversity and ethnicity in Bogot\u00e1}}\n{{Pie chart\n|thumb = right\n|caption = Race and Ethnicity in Bogot\u00e1<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dane.gov.co/index.php/estadisticas-por-tema/demografia-y-poblacion/grupos-etnicos/informacion-tecnica |title=Ethnic groupd|date= |website=www.dane.gov.co |format=PDF|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n|label1=[[White Colombians|White]] and [[Mestizo Colombians|Mestizo]]\n|value1 = 98.8\n|color1 = #008080\n\n|label2=[[Afro-Colombian]] (includes [[Mulatto|Mixed]])\n|value2 = 0.9\n|color2 = #FFBF00\n\n|label3=[[Indigenous peoples in Colombia|American Indian]]\n|value3 = 0.3\n|color3 = #1C39BB\n}}\nThe ethnic composition of the city's population includes minorities of [[Afro-Colombian]] people (0.9%), and [[Indigenous peoples in Colombia|Indigenous Amerindians]] (0.3%); 98.8% of the population has no ethnic affiliation,<ref name=\"auto\"/> but are [[mestizo]]s and whites.{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nThe native population of Bogota (bogotanos), is composed of two large groups: rolos and cachacos, the first being descendants of people who are not native to Bogota and the second, children of bogotanos.\n\nIn Bogot\u00e1, the accelerated urbanization process is not exclusively due to industrialization, since there are complex political and social reasons such as poverty and violence, which have motivated migration from the countryside to the city throughout the 20th century, determining an exponential growth of the population in Bogot\u00e1 and the establishment of misery belts in its surroundings. According to the Consultancy for Human Rights, Codhes, in the period 1999-2005 more than 260,000 displaced persons arrived in Bogot\u00e1, approximately 3.8% of the total population of Bogot\u00e1. The locations where the majority of the displaced population is concentrated are Ciudad Bolivar, Kennedy, Bosa and Usme. For this reason, the children of the migrant population born in Bogot\u00e1 (rolos) often do not have a sense of belonging to the city or a cultural identity as marked as that of the cachacos. However, due to the growing acculturation of rolos and the decreasing number of ethnic cachacos in Bogot\u00e1, the\u00a0 population of rolos tends to be predominant in the city\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Ethnic and demographic evolution of Bogot\u00e1\n| rowspan=\"2\" |'''Year'''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |'''Pop.'''\n| colspan=\"2\" |'''Bogota natives'''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |'''Other colombians'''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |'''Foreigners'''\n|-\n|'''Rolos'''\n|'''Cachacos'''\n|-\n|'''1951'''\n|715.250\n|10.729\n|693.793\n|8047\n|2682\n|-\n|'''1964'''\n|1.697.311\n|135.785\n|1.425.741\n|101.839\n|33.946\n|-\n|'''1973'''\n|2.855.065\n|356.883\n|2.141.299\n|267.662\n|89.221\n|-\n|'''1985'''\n|4.236.490\n|783.751\n|2.668.989\n|587.813\n|195.938\n|-\n|'''1993'''\n|5.484.244\n|1.233.955\n|3.016.334\n|925.466\n|308.489\n|-\n|'''2005'''\n|6.778.691\n|1.931.927\n|2.914.837\n|1.448.945\n|482.982\n|-\n|'''2018'''\n|7.412.566\n|2.594.398\n|2.223.770\n|1.945.799\n|648.600\n|-\n|'''2020'''\n|7.743.955\n|2.787.824\n|2.168.307\n|2.090.868\n|696.956\n|}\n\n=== Crime ===\nBogot\u00e1 has gone to great lengths to change its formerly notorious crime rate and its image with increasing success after being considered in the 1990s to be one of the most violent cities in the world.<ref>{{cite web |year= 2005 |url= http://www.comunidadesegura.org/?q=en/node/32000 |title= Bogot\u00e1's lesson in crime fighting |publisher= Comunidad Segura |accessdate= 2008-12-28 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181127064701/https://www.comunidadesegura.org/?q=en%2Fnode%2F32000 |archive-date= 27 November 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref> In 1993 there were 4,352 murders at a rate of 81 per 100,000 people;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.institut-gouvernance.org/en/conference/fiche-conference-36.html |title=Seguridad, ciudadan\u00eda y pol\u00edticas p\u00fablicas en Bogot\u00e1 |publisher=IRG |accessdate=29 December 2008 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090622012727/http://www.institut-gouvernance.org/en/conference/fiche-conference-36.html |archivedate=22 June 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> in 2007 Bogot\u00e1 suffered 1,401 murders at a rate of 20 per 100,000 inhabitants, and had a further reduction to 14 per 100,000 inhabitants in 2017 (the lowest since 1979).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eltiempo.com/bogota/bogota-confirma-baja-historica-en-tasa-de-homicidios-en-2017-167202|title=Bogot\u00e1 confirma baja hist\u00f3rica en tasa de homicidios|publisher=El Tiempo|accessdate=2 January 2018|language=spanish|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103034159/http://www.eltiempo.com/bogota/bogota-confirma-baja-historica-en-tasa-de-homicidios-en-2017-167202|archive-date=3 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eltiempo.com/colombia/bogota/expertos-analizan-ndice-de-homicidios-en-bogot_12497841-4 |title=Homicidios |format=PDF |page=36 |publisher=El Tiempos |accessdate=29 December 2008 |language=spanish |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130620035628/http://www.eltiempo.com/colombia/bogota/expertos-analizan-ndice-de-homicidios-en-bogot_12497841-4 |archive-date=20 June 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medicinalegal.gov.co/drip/2007/2%20Forensis%202007%20homicidio-1.pdf |title=Homicidios |page=36 |publisher=Instituto Nacional de Medicina Legal y Ciencias Forenses |accessdate=29 December 2008 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217232140/http://www.medicinalegal.gov.co/drip/2007/2%20Forensis%202007%20homicidio-1.pdf |archivedate=17 December 2008 |df=dmy }}</ref> This success was mainly the result of a participatory and integrated security policy; \"Comunidad Segura\", that was first adopted in 1995 and continues to be enforced.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.eltiempo.com/colombia/bogota/ARCHIVO/ARCHIVO-9100821-0.pdf |title=ENCUESTA DE PERCEPCI\u00d3N Y VICTIMIZACI\u00d3NBOGOT\u00c1 Y LAS LOCALIDADES | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111204220201/http://www.eltiempo.com/colombia/bogota/ARCHIVO/ARCHIVO-9100821-0.pdf |archive-date=4 December 2011 |language=Spanish}}</ref> 1.2 percent of street addresses account for 99 percent of homicides.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://igarape.org.br/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/Criminalidad-urbana-en-Colombia-diciembre-2014.pdf |title= Un an\u00e1lisis de la criminalidad urbana en Colombia |page= 39 |publisher= igarape.org.br |accessdate= 13 February 2018 |language= spanish |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180527104538/https://igarape.org.br/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/Criminalidad-urbana-en-Colombia-diciembre-2014.pdf |archive-date= 27 May 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n== Government ==\nBogot\u00e1 is the capital of the [[Colombia|Republic of Colombia]], and houses the [[Congress of Colombia|Congress]], [[Supreme Court of Justice of Colombia|Supreme Court of Justice]] and the center of the executive administration as well as the residence of the [[President of Colombia|President]] ([[Casa de Nari\u00f1o]]).<ref>{{cite web |year= 2007 |url= http://www.bogota.gov.co/portel/libreria/php/frame_detalle.php?h_id=21539&patron=01.11 |title= Bogot\u00e1 se consolida como centro para la inversi\u00f3n extranjera |publisher= Alcald\u00eda Mayor de Bogota |accessdate= 29 December 2008 |language= Spanish |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110727233740/http://www.bogota.gov.co/portel/libreria/php/frame_detalle.php?h_id=21539&patron=01.11 |archive-date= 27 July 2011 |url-status= dead }}</ref> These buildings, along with the Office of the Mayor, the Lievano Palace (Palacio Li\u00e9vano), are located within a few meters from each other on the [[Bol\u00edvar Square]] (Plaza de Bol\u00edvar). The square is located in the city's historical center, [[La Candelaria]], which features architecture in [[Spanish Colonial style|Spanish Colonial]] and [[Spanish Baroque architecture|Spanish Baroque]] styles.\n\nThe [[List of mayors of Bogot\u00e1|Mayor of Bogot\u00e1]] and the [[Bogot\u00e1 City Council|City Council]] \u2013 both elected by popular vote \u2013 are responsible for city administration. In 2015 [[Enrique Pe\u00f1alosa]] was elected Mayor; his term runs from 2016 to 2019.\n\nThe city is divided into 20 localities: [[Usaqu\u00e9n]], [[Chapinero]], [[Santa Fe (Bogot\u00e1)|Santa Fe]], [[San Crist\u00f3bal (Bogot\u00e1)|San Crist\u00f3bal]], [[Usme]], [[Tunjuelito]], [[Bosa (Bogot\u00e1)|Bosa]], [[Kennedy (Bogot\u00e1)|Kennedy]], [[Fontib\u00f3n]], [[Engativ\u00e1]], [[Suba (Bogot\u00e1)|Suba]], [[Barrios Unidos]], [[Teusaquillo]], [[Los M\u00e1rtires]], [[Antonio Nari\u00f1o (Bogot\u00e1)|Antonio Nari\u00f1o]], [[Puente Aranda]], [[La Candelaria]], [[Rafael Uribe Uribe, Bogot\u00e1|Rafael Uribe Uribe]], [[Ciudad Bol\u00edvar (Bogot\u00e1)|Ciudad Bol\u00edvar]] and [[Sumapaz (Bogot\u00e1)|Sumapaz]].\n\nEach of the 20 localities is governed by an administrative board elected by popular vote, made up of no fewer than seven members. The Mayor designates local mayors from candidates nominated by the respective administrative board.\n\n== Economy ==\n\n[[File:Bogot\u00e1 panorama viewed from Torre Colpatria.jpg|upright=3.65|thumb|centre|Panorama of Downtown Bogot\u00e1]]\n\nBogot\u00e1 is the main economic and industrial center of Colombia.\nThe Colombian government fosters the import of capital goods, Bogot\u00e1 being one of the main destinations of these imports.\n\nIn 2016 the World Cities Study Group and Network (GaWC) from the United Kingdom ranked Bogot\u00e1 as an Alpha\u2212World City in the World Cities Study Group's inventory, a high-ranking. Alpha and Alpha- cities are important world cities that link major economic regions into the world economy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lboro.ac.uk/gawc/world2016t.html|title=GaWC \u2013 The World According to GaWC 2016|work=lboro.ac.uk|access-date=15 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131010004859/http://www.lboro.ac.uk/gawc/world2010t.html|archive-date=10 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Tourism ===\nTravel & Tourism's share of the city's overall GDP stands at 2.5%.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.wttc.org/-/media/files/reports/economic-impact-research/city-reports/latin-america-city-travel-and-tourism-impact-2017.pdf?la=en|title= Latin America City Travel and Tourism Impact 2017|publisher= wttc.org|accessdate= 30 November 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171130125301/https://www.wttc.org/-/media/files/reports/economic-impact-research/city-reports/latin-america-city-travel-and-tourism-impact-2017.pdf?la=en|archive-date= 30 November 2017|url-status= live}}</ref> Bogot\u00e1 is responsible for 56% of the tourism that arrives to Colombia and is home 1,423 [[multinational companies]]. Bogot\u00e1 also ranked highly as a global city where [[business]] is done and meetings are held. Bogot\u00e1 is a growing international meetings destination.<ref name = \"BestCities\">{{Cite web|url= http://www.traveldailynews.com/post/bogota-becomes-full-alliance-partner-of-bestcities-global-alliance|title= Bogota becomes full alliance partner of BestCities Global Alliance|publisher= traveldailynews.com|accessdate= 26 May 2016|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160527013351/http://www.traveldailynews.com/post/bogota-becomes-full-alliance-partner-of-bestcities-global-alliance|archive-date= 27 May 2016|url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.bestcities.net/Bogota.aspx|title= Bogot\u00e1, Colombia Profile|publisher= bestcities.net|accessdate= 26 May 2016|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160625064626/http://www.bestcities.net/Bogota.aspx|archive-date= 25 June 2016|url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nDuring the last year, Bogot\u00e1 has won 50 major international events, with 12 more world-class events in progress.<ref name = \"BestCities\"/> The 16th [[World Summit of Nobel Peace Laureates]] took place from 2 to 5 February 2017 in Bogot\u00e1, Colombia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bogota-nobelpeacesummit.com/index.php/es/|title=World Summit of Nobel Peace Laureates|publisher=bogota-nobelpeacesummit.com|accessdate=8 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171008104428/http://www.bogota-nobelpeacesummit.com/index.php/es/|archive-date=8 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[One Young World]] is the preeminent global forum for young leaders aged 18\u201330. Bogot\u00e1, Colombia is the host city for Summit 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oneyoungworld.com/summit-2017/bogota-agenda|title=One Young World 2017 Bogot\u00e1 Agenda|publisher=oneyoungworld.com|accessdate=8 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171008104708/https://www.oneyoungworld.com/summit-2017/bogota-agenda|archive-date=8 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Andino, entrada por la carrera 12.JPG|thumb|The [[Centro Andino]].]]\nThe hotels in the historical center of La Candelaria and its surrounding areas cater to lovers of culture and the arts. This area also has the bulk of hostels in the city as well. In La Candelaria, there are many museums, including the [[Botero Museum]] and the [[Gold Museum, Bogot\u00e1|Gold Museum]]. Close to La Candelaria is the Cerro [[Monserrate]], which you can reach by cable car or funicular. The hotels located near Ciudad Salitre are intended for visitors who make short stops in Bogot\u00e1 and near [[El Dorado International Airport]].\n\nImportant landmarks and tourist stops in Bogot\u00e1 include the [[Bogot\u00e1 Botanical Garden|botanical garden Jos\u00e9 Celestino Mutis]], the [[Quinta de Bol\u00edvar]], the national observatory, the [[Planetarium of Bogot\u00e1|planetarium]], [[Maloka Museum|Maloka]], the Colpatria observation point, the observation point of [[La Calera, Cundinamarca|La Calera]], the monument of the American flags, and La Candelaria (the historical district of the city). There is also Usaquen, a colonial landmark where brunch and flea market on Sundays is a traditional activity. The city has numerous green parks and amusement parks like Salitre Magico or Mundo Aventura.\n\nGreen areas surrounding Bogota are perfect locations for eco-tourism and hiking activities, in the eastern mountains of the city, just a few minutes walking from main roads, there are Quebrada La vieja and Chapinero Waterfalls, two of many green spots for sightseeing and tourism with clean air.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Chapinero waterfalls \u2013 Hiking a secret place in Bogot\u00e1 \u2013 Review of Andes EcoTours, Bogota, Colombia \u2013 TripAdvisor|url = http://www.tripadvisor.com/ShowUserReviews-g294074-d3644534-r151966535-Andes_EcoTours-Bogota.html|website = www.tripadvisor.com|accessdate = 2015-09-17|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150912120747/http://www.tripadvisor.com/ShowUserReviews-g294074-d3644534-r151966535-Andes_EcoTours-Bogota.html|archive-date = 12 September 2015|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Alameda de Quebrada Vieja (Bogota, Colombia): Address, Hiking Trail Reviews \u2013 TripAdvisor|url = http://www.tripadvisor.com/Attraction_Review-g294074-d7762329-Reviews-Alameda_de_Quebrada_Vieja-Bogota.html|website = www.tripadvisor.com|accessdate = 2015-09-17|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151009232655/http://www.tripadvisor.com/Attraction_Review-g294074-d7762329-Reviews-Alameda_de_Quebrada_Vieja-Bogota.html|archive-date = 9 October 2015|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nThere are also several areas of the city where fine restaurants can be found. The G Zone, the T Zone, and La Macarena are well known for their gastronomic offerings.<ref>{{in lang|es}} [http://www.eltiempo.com/multimedia/especiales/vitrina-de-anato-10-restaurantes-para-visitar-en-bogota/15295571 \"Ten restaurants to visit in Bogot\u00e1\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160901125751/http://www.eltiempo.com/multimedia/especiales/vitrina-de-anato-10-restaurantes-para-visitar-en-bogota/15295571 |date=1 September 2016 }} ''El Tiempo'' 26-02-2015</ref>\n\nSince the 2000s, major hotel chains have established in the city. Bogota has a great cultural diversity, coming from different regions of the country, which allows the tourist to know the multiculturalism of the country without the need to travel to other cities, this includes gastronomy and different festivals.\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:2019 Bogot\u00e1 - Iglesia de Monserrate.jpg|Monserrate Sanctuary, a local landmark\nFile:Tga bogota 0427-1hgbbatlantis plaza3.jpg|Atlantis Plaza Mall, featuring the [[Hard Rock Cafe]]\nFile:Bogota, Colombia (25187139147).jpg|[[La Candelaria]], the historical district of the city\nFile:Domo de Maloka.jpg|Maloka\n</gallery>\n\n=== Shopping malls ===\n[[File:CC Parque La Colina Bogot\u00e1 N sep 2017 (1).jpg|thumb|Parque La Colina Shopping Mall]]\n\nBogot\u00e1's economy has been significantly boosted due to new shopping malls built within the last few years. {{as of|2011|December|}}, over 160 new malls are planned in addition to the existing 100 malls.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://links.org.au/node/2673 |title=Colombia rising? &#124; Links International Journal of Socialist Renewal |publisher=Links.org.au |access-date=5 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108041750/http://links.org.au/node/2673 |archive-date=8 January 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Notable malls include:\n* [[Centro Andino]]\n* [[Centro Mayor]]\n* [[Centro Comercial Santafe|Santaf\u00e9]]\n* [[Gran Estaci\u00f3n]]\n* [[Portal de la 80]]\n* [[:es:Centro comercial Tit\u00e1n Plaza|Tit\u00e1n Plaza]]\n* [[:es:Centro Comercial Calima|Calima]]\n* [[:es:Centro Comercial Atlantis Plaza|Atlantis Plaza]]\n* [[:es:Unicentro|Unicentro]]\n* [[:es:Centro Comercial Hayuelos|Hayuelos]]\n\n== Media ==\nBogota is home to [[:Template:Bogot\u00e1 TV|several television stations]] like [[Canal Capital]] and [[Citytv Bogot\u00e1|Citytv]] which are local stations, [[Canal 13 (Colombia)|Canal 13]] is a regional station, and is home to the national channels [[Caracol TV]], [[RCN TV]], [[Canal Uno (Colombia)|Canal Uno]], [[Canal Institucional]], and [[Se\u00f1al Colombia]]. It has multiple satellite television services like [[Telef\u00f3nica]], [[Claro Americas|Claro]] and [[DirecTV]] and several satellite dishes which offer hundreds of international channels, plus several exclusive channels for Bogot\u00e1.\n\nIn Bogota, all the major radio networks in the country are available, in both AM and FM; 70% of the FM stations offer [[Radio Data System|RDS service]].\nThere are several newspapers, including ''[[El Tiempo (Colombia)|El Tiempo]]'', ''[[El Espectador]]'' and ''[[El Nuevo Siglo]]'', plus economical dailies ''La Rep\u00fablica'' and ''Portafolio'', tabloids ''El Espacio'', ''Q'Hubo'', and ''Extra''. Bogot\u00e1 also offers three free newspapers, two Spanish, ADN and [[Publimetro]], and one English, The Bogota Post.\n\n== Infrastructure ==\n[[File:Avenida Caracas calle 40 A Casa de ladrillo.JPG|thumb|An old house in the [[Teusaquillo]] locality, near downtown Bogot\u00e1 (''Estrato 4'')]]\n\nEnergy and sewer bills are stratified based on the location of owner's residence,<ref>{{cite web|year=2008 |url=http://www.gobiernobogota.gov.co/component/option,com_docman/task,doc_details/Itemid,/gid,432/ |title=Proyecto de Acuerdo 651 de 2008 |publisher=Secretaria de Gobierno de Bogot\u00e1 |accessdate=29 December 2008 |language=Spanish }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The system is the classification of the residential properties that should receive public services.<ref name=\"estrato\">CONGRESO DE COLOMBIA. Ley 142 de 1994 (julio 11), art\u00edculo 102.</ref> Although the system does not consider the income per person and the rules say that the residential real estate should stratify and not households.<ref name = \"Preguntas frecuentes estratificaci\u00f3n\">{{cite web|title= Preguntas_frecuentes_estratificaci\u00f3n|url= https://www.dane.gov.co/files/geoestadistica/Preguntas_frecuentes_estratificacion.pdf|publisher= dane.gov.co|access-date= 18 December 2016|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120524171019/http://www.dane.gov.co/files/geoestadistica/Preguntas_frecuentes_estratificacion.pdf|archive-date= 24 May 2012|url-status= live}}</ref> All mayors should do the stratification of residential properties of their municipality or district.<ref name=\"estrato\"/>\n\nBogot\u00e1's social strata have been divided as follows and have been extensively used by the government as a reference to develop social welfare programs, statistical information and to some degree for the assignment of lands.\n* Estrato 1 (lowest)\n* Estrato 2 (low)\n* Estrato 3 (mid-low)\n* Estrato 4 (mid-high)\n* Estrato 5 (high)\n* Estrato 6 (highest)\n{{clear}}\n\n== Transport ==\n\n[[File:TransMilenio Bogota Map.png|thumb|Map of the [[TransMilenio]] system.]]\nBogot\u00e1's growth has placed a strain on its roads and highways, but since 1998 significant efforts to upgrade the infrastructure have been undertaken.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldbank.org/en/results/2015/08/13/better-transport-water-and-sanitation-for-the-urban-poor-in-bogota|title=Better Transport, Water and Sanitation for the Urban Poor in Bogot\u00e1|website=Worldbank.org|accessdate=19 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518025854/http://www.worldbank.org/en/results/2015/08/13/better-transport-water-and-sanitation-for-the-urban-poor-in-bogota|archive-date=18 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Private car ownership forms a major part of the congestion, in addition to taxis, buses and commercial vehicles. Buses remain the main means of mass transit. There are two bus systems: the traditional system and the [[TransMilenio]].\n\nThe traditional system runs a variety of bus types, operated by several companies on normal streets and avenues: ''Bus'' (large buses), ''Buseta'' (medium size buses) and ''Colectivo'' (vans or minivans). The bigger buses were divided into two categories: ''Ejecutivo'', which was originally to be a deluxe service and was not to carry standing passengers, and ''corriente'' or normal service. Since May 2008, all buses run as ''corriente'' services. Bogot\u00e1 is a [[Transportation hub|hub]] for domestic and international bus routes. The Bogot\u00e1 terminal serves routes to most cities and towns in Colombia<ref>{{cite web |year= 2008 |url= http://www.bogota-dc.com/trans/terminal.htm |title= Bogot\u00e1 Transportation Terminal & Train Station |publisher= Bogot\u00e1-dc.com |accessdate= 29 December 2008 |language= Spanish |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20081224032444/http://www.bogota-dc.com/trans/terminal.htm |archive-date= 24 December 2008 |url-status= live }}</ref> and is the largest in the country. There is international service to Ecuador, Per\u00fa and Venezuela.\n\nThe [[TransMilenio]] system was created during [[Enrique Pe\u00f1alosa]]'s mayoral term,<ref>{{cite web |year= 2008 |url= http://www.elespectador.com/noticias/bogota/articulo-millonaria-condena-al-distrito-fallas-transmilenio |title= Millonaria condena al Distrito por fallas en Transmilenio |publisher= El Espectador |accessdate= 29 December 2008 |language= Spanish |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110216163714/http://elespectador.com/noticias/bogota/articulo-millonaria-condena-al-distrito-fallas-transmilenio |archive-date= 16 February 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref> and is a form of [[bus rapid transit]] that has been deployed as a measure to compensate for the lack of a subway or rail system. TransMilenio combines articulated buses that operate on dedicated bus roads (busways) and smaller buses (feeders) that operate in residential areas, bringing passengers to the main grid. TransMilenio's main routes are: Caracas Avenue, Northern Highway (''Autopista Norte''), 80th Street, Americas Avenue, Jim\u00e9nez Avenue, and 30th Avenue (also referred to as ''Norte Quito Sur'' or ''N.Q.S.'' for short). Routes for Suba Avenue and Southern Highway (''Autopista Sur''), the southern leg of the 30th Avenue, were opened in April 2006. The third phase of the system will cover 7th Avenue, 10th Avenue, and 26th Street (or ''Avenida El Dorado''). The system is planned to cover the entire city by 2030. Although the Transmilenio carries commuters to numerous corners of the city, it is more expensive (US$0.80 or 2300 COP) than any public transport, except taxis.\n\nIn addition to TransMilenio, the Pe\u00f1alosa administration and voter-approved referenda helped to establish travel restrictions on cars with certain license plate numbers during peak hours called [[Pico y placa]]; {{convert|121|km|0|abbr=off}} of [[Ciclov\u00eda]] on Sundays and major holidays; a massive system ({{convert|376|km|0|abbr=on}} {{As of|2013|lc=y}}) of bicycle paths and segregated lanes called ''[[Bogot\u00e1's Bike Paths Network|ciclorrutas]]''; and the removal of thousands of parking spots in an attempt to make roads more pedestrian-friendly and discourage car use. ''Ciclorrutas'' is one of the most extensive dedicated bike path networks of any city in the world, with a total extension of {{convert|376|km|0|abbr=off}}. It extends from the north of the city, 170th Street, to the south, 27th Street, and from [[Monserrate]] on the east to the [[Bogot\u00e1 River]] on the west. The ''ciclorruta'' was started by the 1995\u20131998 [[Antanas Mockus]] administration with a few kilometers, and considerably extended afterwards with the development of a Bicycle Master Plan and the addition of paths hundreds of kilometers in extent.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.cambio.com.co/paiscambio/762/ARTICULO-WEB-NOTA_INTERIOR_CAMBIO-3948271.html |title= Bogotanos olvidaron para qu\u00e9 fue creado el D\u00eda sin carro |publisher= Cambio |accessdate= 29 December 2008 |date= 2 November 2008 |language= Spanish |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080820102143/http://www.cambio.com.co/paiscambio/762/ARTICULO-WEB-NOTA_INTERIOR_CAMBIO-3948271.html |archivedate= 20 August 2008 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> Since the construction of the ''ciclorruta'' bicycle use in the city has increased, and a car free week was introduced in 2014.<ref name=greenblog>{{cite news |last1=King |first1=Danny |title=Bogota citizens give up automobiles in first ever Car Free Week |url=http://green.autoblog.com/2014/02/26/bogota-citizens-give-up-automobiles-first-ever-car-free-week/ |accessdate=28 August 2014 |agency=autobloggreen |publisher=green.autoblog.com |date=26 February 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819223148/http://green.autoblog.com/2014/02/26/bogota-citizens-give-up-automobiles-first-ever-car-free-week/ |archive-date=19 August 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Articulado de Transmilenio en el Eje Ambiental.JPG|Bi-articulated [[TransMilenio]] bus\nFile:Bogot\u00e1 - Bus del SITP por la carrera 11.jpg|Urban (SITP) bus, part of the integrated public transport system\nFile:Bogot\u00e1 - Centro Inernacional Ciclorruta cl 10.JPG|Bikepath in central Bogota\nFile:Trancon Autonorte.jpg|Traffic on the Northern Highway (Autopista Norte)\n</gallery>\n\n=== Airports ===\n[[File:Aeropuerto Bogot\u00e1.JPG|thumb|[[El Dorado International Airport]]]]\nBogot\u00e1's main airport is [[El Dorado International Airport]], with an approximate area of {{cvt|6.9|km2}} located west of the city's downtown in the [[Fontib\u00f3n]] Locality. It is the third most important airport in Latin America after [[Mexico City International Airport]] and [[S\u00e3o Paulo\u2013Guarulhos International Airport]] and it is the most important airport in Colombia. Construction of the airport was ordered by [[Gustavo Rojas Pinilla]] (19th President of Colombia) in 1955 to replace the [[:es:Aeropuerto de Techo|Aeropuerto de Techo]]. Due to its central location in Colombia and in Latin America, it is a hub for Colombia's Flagship Carrier [[Avianca]], [[Copa Airlines Colombia]] and [[LATAM Colombia]]. It is also serviced by a number of international airlines including American, Delta, United, Air France, KLM, Turkish Airlines, Jet Blue, and Lufthansa. The national airport has begun to take more responsibility due to the congestion at the international airport. In response to the high demand of approximately 27 Million passengers per year,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ifly.com/bogota-eldorado-airport|title=Bogota El Nuevo Dorado BOG Airport \u2013 Bogota, Colombia|work=ifly.com|access-date=2 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150521172031/http://www.ifly.com/bogota-eldorado-airport|archive-date=21 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> a new airport, El Dorado II, is planned to be built by 2021, to help alleviate traffic at the main airport.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bogota to have second airport by 2021|url=http://colombiareports.co/bogota-second-airport-2021/|website=Colombia Reports|accessdate=1 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150316152829/http://colombiareports.co/bogota-second-airport-2021/|archive-date=16 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA secondary airport, [[Military Transport Air Command (Colombian Air Force)|CATAM]], serves as a base for Military and Police Aviation. This airport, which uses the runways of El Dorado will eventually move to Madrid, a nearby town in the region of Cundinamarca, leaving further space to expand El Dorado.<ref>{{cite web |year=2013 |url=http://colombiareports.co/colombia-to-move-air-force-base-expand-bogota-airport/ |title=Colombia to move military airbase to expand El Dorado airport |publisher=Colombia Reports |accessdate=9 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109135011/http://colombiareports.co/colombia-to-move-air-force-base-expand-bogota-airport/ |archive-date=9 January 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[Guaymaral Airport]] is another small airport located in the northern boundaries of Bogota. It is used mainly for private aviation activities.\n\n=== Urban and suburban railways ===\n{{Main|Bogot\u00e1 Metro|Tramways of Bogot\u00e1}}\n{{See also|Bogot\u00e1's Savannah Railway|RegioTram}}\nBogot\u00e1 has little railway transit infrastructure, following the collapse of the tram network, although a number of plans hope to change that. The [[Bogot\u00e1 Metro]] has been pushed forward by two successive governments, and proponents hope that construction will soon begin. Plans to construct railways in and out of the city, replacing defunct routes, have been delayed due to the pressing need for transport within the city.<ref>[http://www.elespectador.com/impreso/articuloimpreso90115-se-mueve-el-tren-de-cercanias Se mueve el tren de cercan\u00edas] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924070634/http://www.elespectador.com/impreso/articuloimpreso90115-se-mueve-el-tren-de-cercanias |date=24 September 2015 }}, [[El Espectador]], 12 November 2008</ref> A [[tram train]] line using right-of-way from the defunct Bogot\u00e1 Savannah Railway, known as [[RegioTram]], will be opening in 2023.\n\n=== Bicycle infrastructure ===\n{{Main|Bogot\u00e1's Bike Paths Network}}\nBogot\u00e1 is the Colombian city with the most extensive and comprehensive network of bike paths. Bogot\u00e1's bike paths network or Ciclorutas de Bogot\u00e1 in Spanish, designed and built during the administration of Mayors [[Antanas Mockus]] and [[Enrique Pe\u00f1alosa]], is also one of the most extensive in the world and the most extensive in Latin America.<ref>{{cite book |title=Colombia |last=Woods |first=Sarah |page=123 |year=2012 |publisher=[[Bradt Travel Guides]] |isbn=9781841623641 }}</ref> The network is integrated with the [[TransMilenio]] bus system which has bicycle parking facilities.\n\nBogota implemented a healthy habit called \"Ciclovia\" where principal highways are closed from 7:00&nbsp;a.m. until 2:00 pm on Sundays and public holidays; therefore, the People ride their bikes to enjoy the city as well as exercise. In the same way just on December the same activity is carried out in the night, there are some special activities such as fireworks, street theater performances, and street food just to mention a few.\n\nSince 4 April 2016 the [[carrera 11]] has been reduced from four to three car lanes and a new bike lane (''cicloruta'') has been inaugurated.<ref>{{in lang|es}} [http://www.elespectador.com/noticias/bogota/carrera-11-bogota-volvera-ser-un-solo-sentido-articulo-611894 Carrera 11 de 4 a 3 carriles con un carril doble sentido para bicicletas] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403185808/http://www.elespectador.com/noticias/bogota/carrera-11-bogota-volvera-ser-un-solo-sentido-articulo-611894 |date=3 April 2016 }} \u2013 [[Caracol Radio]] \u2013 accessed 25-04-2016</ref>\n\n=== Tramway ===\nOn 25 December 1884, the first tramway pulled by mules was inaugurated and covered the route from [[Bol\u00edvar Square|Plaza de Bol\u00edvar]] to Chapinero,<ref name=\"PorupRaub2009\">{{cite book |author1=Porup, Jens |author2=Raub, Kevin |author3=Reid, Robert |title=Colombia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Kw78V-p1aY4C&pg=PA63 |access-date=10 March 2013 |date=6 June 2009 |publisher=Lonely Planet |isbn=978-1-74220-326-3 |pages=63\u2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130620222901/http://books.google.com/books?id=Kw78V-p1aY4C&pg=PA63 |archive-date=20 June 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> and in 1892, the line connecting Plaza de Bol\u00edvar and La Sabana Station started operating. The tramway ran over wooden rails and was easily derailed, so steel rails imported from England were eventually installed. In 1894, a tramway car ran the Bogot\u00e1\u2013Chapinero line every 20 minutes. {{Citation needed|date=November 2015}} The tram system eventually grew to cover most of the city and its surrounding suburbs. But during the [[Bogotazo]] riots of 1948, the system suffered heavy damage and was forced to close. The economic effects of the [[La Violencia|subsequent civil war]] that followed prevented the damage from being repaired. Parts of the system continued to operate in a reduced state until 1951, when they were replaced by buses. Most of the streetcar tracks were eventually paved over, but exposed tracks can still be seen on many of the older roads of the city, especially downtown and in the [[La Candelaria]] area, although it has been about 70 years{{When|date=October 2017}} since any vehicles have run on them.\n\n===Bogota public transportation statistics===\nThe average amount of time people spend commuting with public transit in Bogota, for example to and from work, on a weekday is 97 min. 32% of public transit riders, ride for more than 2 hours every day. The average amount of time people wait at a stop or station for public transit is 20 min, while 40% of riders wait for over 20 minutes on average every day. The average distance people usually ride in a single trip with public transit is 8&nbsp;km, while 16% travel for over 12&nbsp;km in a single direction.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bogota Public Transportation Statistics|publisher=Global Public Transit Index by Moovit|url=https://moovitapp.com/insights/en/Moovit_Insights_Public_Transit_Index_Colombia_Bogota-762|accessdate=19 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901030329/https://moovitapp.com/insights/en/Moovit_Insights_Public_Transit_Index_Colombia_Bogota-762|archive-date=1 September 2017|url-status=live}} [[File:CC-BY icon.svg|50px]] Material was copied from this source, which is available under a [https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/ Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171016050101/https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/ |date=16 October 2017 }}.</ref>\n\n== Education ==\n{{Main|List of universities in Bogot\u00e1}}\n\nKnown as the Athens of South America,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.drclas.harvard.edu/revista/articles/view/242 |title=Colombia |publisher=Drclas.harvard.edu |accessdate=2009-07-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090703145510/http://www.drclas.harvard.edu/revista/articles/view/242 |archivedate=3 July 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Bogot\u00e1 has an extensive educational system of both primary and secondary schools and colleges. Due to the constant migration of people into the nation's capital, the availability of quotas for access to education offered by the State free of charge is often insufficient. The city also has a diverse system of colleges and private schools.\n\nThere are a number of universities, both public and private. In 2002, there were a total of 113 higher education institutions; in Bogot\u00e1 there are several universities, most partially or fully accredited by the NAC (National Accreditation Council): [[National University of Colombia]], [[University of the Andes, Colombia]], [[District University of Bogot\u00e1]], [[La Salle University, Colombia]], [[University of La Sabana]], [[Pontifical Xavierian University]], [[Our Lady of the Rosary University]], [[Universidad Externado de Colombia]], [[Military University Nueva Granada]], [[Central University (Colombia)|Central University, Colombia]], [[University of America]], [[Sergio Arboleda University]], [[Jorge Tadeo Lozano University]], [[Pilot University of Colombia]], [[Catholic University of Colombia]], [[Saint Thomas Aquinas University]] and [[National Pedagogic University (Colombia)|Universidad Pedag\u00f3gica Nacional]].\n\nThe city has a University City at the National University of Colombia campus located in the traditional sector Teusaquillo. It is the largest campus in Colombia and one of the largest in Latin America.\n\n<gallery class=\"centre\" widths=\"200\" heights=\"150\">\nFile:Fray Crist\u00f3bal de Torres.JPG|\"El Claustro\" at the [[Del Rosario University]]\nFile:UNLuis carlos sarmiento angulo.jpg|Building of Science and Technology \"Luis Carlos Sarmiento\" at the [[National University of Colombia]]\nFile:Centro \u00c1tico.JPG|Centro \u00c1tico at [[Pontifical Xavierian University]]\nFile:Universidad de los Andes (3326108271).jpg|Mario Laserna building in the [[University of Los Andes (Colombia)|University of the Andes]]\n</gallery>\n\n== Culture ==\n[[File:Ciclov\u00eda por la Carrera S\u00e9ptima.jpg|thumb|left|[[Ciclov\u00eda]] in Bogot\u00e1]]\nBogot\u00e1 has many cultural venues including 58 museums, 62 art galleries, 33 library networks, 45 stage theaters, 75 sports and attraction parks, and over 150 national monuments.<ref>Colombia Official Tourism Portal [http://www.colombia.travel/en/international-tourist/where-to-go/recommended-weekend-destinations/bogota \"Bogot\u00e1: a city for experiencing culture\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090804174411/http://www.colombia.travel/en/international-tourist/where-to-go/recommended-weekend-destinations/bogota |date=4 August 2009 }}</ref> Many of these are renowned globally such as:\nThe [[Luis \u00c1ngel Arango Library]], the most important in the region{{according to whom|date=September 2015}} which receives well over 6 million visitors a year;<ref>Banco de la Republica [https://web.archive.org/web/20171227122019/http://www.lablaa.org/prensa/boletin_sub_gerencia.pdf \"2008 Press Release\"]. Retrieved 3 September 2009.</ref>\nThe [[Colombian National Museum]], one of the oldest in the Americas, dating back to 1823;<ref>Museo Nacional de Colombia [http://www.museonacional.gov.co/index.php?pag=home&id=6|43|0& \"History\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130606070236/http://www.museonacional.gov.co/index.php?pag=home&id=6%7C43%7C0& |date=6 June 2013 }}. Retrieved 3 September 2009.</ref>\nThe [[Ibero-American Theater Festival]], largest of its kind in the world, receives 2 million attendees enjoying over 450 performances across theaters and off the street;<ref>Colombia Official Tourism Portal [http://www.colombia.travel/en/international-tourist/what-to-do/history-and-tradition/fairs-and-festivals/april/ibero-american-theater-festival-of-bogota \"Ibero-American Theater Festival of Bogot\u00e1: The Largest Theater Showcase in the World\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090605140033/http://www.colombia.travel/en/international-tourist/what-to-do/history-and-tradition/fairs-and-festivals/april/ibero-american-theater-festival-of-bogota |date=5 June 2009 }}</ref>\nThe [[Bogot\u00e1 Philharmonic]] is the most important{{according to whom|date=September 2015}} [[symphony orchestra]] in Colombia, with over 100 musicians and 140 performances a year.<ref>Filarmonica de Bogot\u00e1 [http://www.filarmonicabogota.gov.co/secciones/historia/lineatiempo.htm \"Philarmonic Timeline\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090105174325/http://www.filarmonicabogota.gov.co/secciones/historia/lineatiempo.htm |date=5 January 2009 }}</ref> The city has been a member of the [[Creative Cities Network|UNESCO Creative Cities Network]] in the category of music since March 2012.<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.unesco.org/new/en/media-services/single-view/news/bogota_designated_as_unesco_city_of_music/ |title= Bogota designated as UNESCO City of Music |agency= United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization |website= www.unesco.org |language= en |access-date= 2018-10-03 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181003221108/http://www.unesco.org/new/en/media-services/single-view/news/bogota_designated_as_unesco_city_of_music/ |archive-date= 3 October 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nThe Crist\u00f3bal Col\u00f3n Theater, the country's oldest Opera House, opened in 1892. It is home to the National Symphony Association's major act, the [[National Symphony Orchestra of Colombia]].<ref>Ministerio de Cultura [http://www1.mincultura.gov.co/nuevo/teatro_colon/historia_colon.php \"Cristobal Colon Theater\"]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n[[Rock al Parque]] or Rock at the Park is an open air rock music festival. Recurring annually, it gathers over 320,000 music fans who can enjoy over 60 band performances for free during three days a year.<ref>Rock at the Park [http://www.rockalparque.gov.co/ \"15th Edition of the Concert is over\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091229050323/http://www.rockalparque.gov.co/ |date=29 December 2009 }}</ref> The series have been so successful during its 15 years of operation that the city has replicated the initiative for other music genres, resulting in other recent festivals like Salsa at the Park, Hip Hop at the Park, Ballet at the Park, Opera at the Park, and Jazz at the Park.\n\n[[Kids' Choice Awards Colombia]], are the most important{{according to whom|date=September 2015}} awards given in the city by [[Nickelodeon]] and the first ceremony was given in 2014 by the singer [[Maluma (singer)|Maluma]] and in [[Corferias]] the ceremony has been the home of shows given by artists like [[Austin Mahone]], [[Carlos Pe\u00f1a]], [[Don Tetto]] and [[Riva (singer)|Riva]] among others.\n\nBogot\u00e1 has worked in recent years to position itself as leader in cultural offerings in South America, and it is increasingly being recognized worldwide as a hub in the region for the development of the arts.<ref>Scoop Independent News, New Zealand [http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/WO0704/S00398.htm \"Cultural Diversity Highlighted\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100329033325/http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/WO0704/S00398.htm |date=29 March 2010 }} 24 April 2007</ref><ref>Sun Sentinel, Florida [https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/sun_sentinel/access/993698241.html?dids=993698241:993698241&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT& \"Give Bogota a try (no kidding) citty boasts arts, scenery and great food.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130724083014/http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/sun_sentinel/access/993698241.html?dids=993698241:993698241&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT& |date=24 July 2013 }}, 26 February 2006</ref><ref>Inter Press Service [http://www.ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=36061 \"COLOMBIA: Open Your Books, Please, Bogot\u00e1\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100329030203/http://www.ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=36061 |date=29 March 2010 }}</ref><ref>Noticias de Bogot\u00e1: Arte [http://www.barriosdebogota.com/abrio-las-puertas-la-feria-de-arte-de-bogota-artbo/ \"ArtBo 2009 \u2013 Reportaje\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100330151207/http://www.barriosdebogota.com/abrio-las-puertas-la-feria-de-arte-de-bogota-artbo/ |date=30 March 2010 }}</ref>\nIn 2007, Bogot\u00e1 was awarded the title of Cultural Capital of [[Ibero-America]] by the UCCI ([[Union of Ibero-American Capital Cities]]), and it became the only city to have received the recognition twice, after being awarded for the first time in 1991.<ref>Universia [http://www.universia.net.co/cultura/destacado/bogota-por-segunda-vez-capital-iberoamericana-de-la-cultura.html \"Bogota Ibero-American Capital of Culture for Second Time\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20130101193737/http://www.universia.net.co/cultura/destacado/bogota-por-segunda-vez-capital-iberoamericana-de-la-cultura.html |date=1 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\n=== Cultural history ===\nBogot\u00e1 gave the Spanish-speaking world [[Jos\u00e9 Asunci\u00f3n Silva]] (1865\u20131896), [[Modernism]] pioneer. His poetic work in the novel ''De sobremesa'' has a place in outstanding American literature. [[Rafael Pombo]] (1833\u20131912) was an [[American romanticism]] poet who left a collection of fables essential part of children imagination and Colombian tradition.\n\n=== Architecture ===\n[[File:Construcci\u00f3n del BD Bacat\u00e1.JPG|thumb|upright|[[BD Bacat\u00e1]], under construction, will be the city's tallest building.]]\n\nThe urban morphology and typology of colonial buildings in Bogot\u00e1 have been maintained since the late nineteenth century, long after the independence of Colombia (1810). {{citation needed|date=February 2015}} This persistence of the colonial setting is still visible, particularly in La Candelaria, the historical center of Bogot\u00e1. Also kept up are the colonial houses of two stories, with courtyards, gabled roofs, ceramic tiles and balconies. In some cases, these balconies were enclosed with glass windows during the Republican period, a distinguishing feature of the architecture of the sector (for example, the House of Rafael Pombo).{{Citation needed|date=February 2016}}\n\n\"Republican Architecture\" was the style that prevailed between 1830 and 1930. {{citation needed|date=February 2015}} Although there were attempts to consolidate a modern architectural language, the only examples seen are University City and White City at the National University of Colombia (constructed 1936 to 1939). {{Citation needed|date=May 2014}} This work was developed by German architect [[Leopold Rother]], although architects of rationalist trends participated in the design of campus buildings. We also see in Bogotan architecture trends such as art deco, expressionism and organic architecture. This last trend was typified by Bogotan architects in the second half of the twentieth century such as [[Rogelio Salmona]].\n\nIn 2015 BD Bacat\u00e1 was inaugurated, surpassing the Colpatria Tower to become the tallest building of the city and of Colombia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bdbacata.com/|title=BD Bacat\u00e1 \u2013 Sitio Oficial|work=bdbacata.com|access-date=31 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150328103033/http://bdbacata.com/|archive-date=28 March 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The building its expected to be the beginning of the city's downtown renovation.\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Centro empresarial St b\u00e1rbara Bogot\u00e1.JPG|Santa Barbara business district\nFile:Casas en La Merced, Bogot\u00e1.JPG|[[Victorian architecture]] in [[Teusaquillo]]\nFile:Torres del parque torre B.JPG|Torres del Parque\nFile:La Santa Maria.JPG|Santa Maria [[bullring]]\n</gallery>\n\n=== Libraries and archives ===\nIn 2007 Bogot\u00e1 was named [[World Book Capital]] by [[UNESCO]].<ref>UNESCO [http://portal.unesco.org/culture/en/ev.php-URL_ID=27412&URL_DO=DO_TOPIC&URL_SECTION=201.html \"World Book Capital City\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715195230/http://portal.unesco.org/culture/en/ev.php-URL_ID%3D27412%26URL_DO%3DDO_TOPIC%26URL_SECTION%3D201.html |date=15 July 2019 }} 2007</ref> Bogot\u00e1 is the first Latin American city to receive this recognition, and the second one in the Americas after [[Montreal]]. It stood out in programs, the library network and the presence of organizations that, in a coordinated manner, are working to promote books and reading in the city. Several specific initiatives for the World Book Capital program have been undertaken with the commitment of groups, both public and private, engaged in the book sector.\n\nThe city is home to the Biblored, an institution which administers 16 small and four large public libraries (Biblioteca Virgilio Barco, Biblioteca El Tintal, Biblioteca El Tunal and Biblioteca Julio Mario Santodomingo). It also has six branches of the Library Network of the Family Compensation Fund Colsubsidio and libraries and documentation centers attached to institutions like the Museo Nacional de Colombia (specializing in old books, catalogs and art), Museum of Modern Art, the Alliance Fran\u00e7aise, and the Centro Colombo Americano.\n\nAnother set of libraries are the new collaborative initiatives between the state, city and international agencies. Examples are the Cultural Center Gabriel Garc\u00eda Marquez, custom designed by the Fondo de Cultura Economica in Mexico, and the Spanish Cultural Center, which will begin construction with public funds and of the Spanish government in downtown Bogot\u00e1. {{citation needed|date=January 2014}}\n\nThe [[National Library of Colombia]] (1777), a dependence of the Ministry of Culture and the Biblioteca Luis Angel Arango (1958), a dependence of the Bank of the Republic are the two largest public libraries in the city. The first is the repository of more than two million volumes, with an important collection of ancient books. The latter has almost two million volumes, and with {{convert|45000|m2|sqft|lk=out|abbr=on}} in size, it hosts 10,000 visitors a day; the Library Alfonso Palacio Rudas is also a dependence of the Bank of the Republic, and is located at the north of the city, with about 50,000 volumes. Other large public libraries are the Library of Congress in Colombia (with 100,000 volumes), of the Instituto Caro y Cuervo (with nearly 200,000 volumes, the largest Latin American library in Philology and Linguistics), the Library of the Academy of History The Library of the Academy of Language, the Library of the Colombian Institute of Anthropology and History ICANH, and many university libraries.\n\nBogot\u00e1 is home to historical records housed in the General National Archive, a collection of about 60 million documents, one of the largest repositories of primary historical sources in Latin America. Bogot\u00e1 is also home to the Musical Archive of the Cathedral of Bogot\u00e1 (with thousands of books and choral song-colonial period), the Archdiocesan Archive, the Archive of the Conciliar Seminary of Bogot\u00e1, the Archive History National University of Colombia and the Archive of the Mint in Bogot\u00e1, under the Bank of the Republic.\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Biblioteca nacional Bogot\u00e1.JPG|National Library of Colombia\nFile:Biblioteca Julio Mario Santodomingo .jpg|Julio Mario Santo Domingo Public Library\nFile:Biblioteca Virgilio Barco Bogot\u00e1 Colombia.jpg|Virgilio Barco Public Library\nFile:Biblioteca Tintal.jpg|El Tintal Public Library\n</gallery>\n\n=== Museums and galleries ===\n[[File:Fachada museo nacional.JPG|thumb|National Museum of Colombia]]\n\nThe city offers 58 museums and over 70 art galleries. {{Citation needed|date=April 2015}} The [[Colombian National Museum]] has acquisitions divided into four collections: art, history, archeology and ethnography. The [[Gold Museum, Bogot\u00e1|Gold Museum]], with 35,000 pieces of tumbaga gold, along with 30,000 objects in ceramic, stone and textiles, represents the largest collection of pre-Columbian gold in the world.{{Citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nThe [[Botero Museum]] has 123 works of Fernando Botero and 87 works by international artists. The Museum of Modern Art in Bogot\u00e1 has a collection of graphic arts, industrial design and photography. The Museum of Colonial Art is home to an important collection of colonial art from Colombia. Fundaci\u00f3n Gilberto Alzate Avenda\u00f1o hosts activities related to the performing arts and shows temporary exhibits of art in its halls and galleries.{{Citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nAmong the scientific museums are the Archeological Museum \u2013 Casa del Marqu\u00e9s de San Jorge, which has about 30 thousand pieces of pre-Columbian art, Instituto de Ciencias Naturales (UN), one of the four largest museums of natural sciences in Latin America, and the Geological Museum, which has a collection specializing in Geology and Paleontology.{{Citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nBogot\u00e1 has historical museums like the [[Jorge Eliecer Gaitan Museum]], the Museum of Independence (Museo de la Independencia), the [[Quinta de Bol\u00edvar]] and the Casa Museo Francisco Jos\u00e9 de Caldas, as well as the headquarters of Maloka and the [[Children's Museum of Bogot\u00e1]]. New museums include the Art Deco and the Museum of Bogot\u00e1.{{Citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\n=== Theater and arts ===\n[[File:FITB.jpg|upright=0.85|thumb|[[Ibero-American Theater Festival]]]]\n[[File:Picolontheaterj.jpg|thumb|left|''[[Teatro de Crist\u00f3bal Col\u00f3n]]'' (Christopher Columbus Theater)]]\n\nBesides the [[Ibero-American Theater Festival]], the largest theater festival in the world, the city has forty-five theaters; the principal ones are the [[Teatro de Crist\u00f3bal Col\u00f3n|Colon Theater]], the newly built [[:es:Biblioteca P\u00fablica Julio Mario Santo Domingo|Teatro Mayor Julio Mario Santo Domingo]], the National Theater with its two venues, the traditional TPB Hall, the Theater of La Candelaria, the Camarin del Carmen (over 400 years old, formerly a convent), the Colsubsidio, and a symbol of the city, the renovated [[:es:Teatro Jorge Eli\u00e9cer Gait\u00e1n|Teatro Jorge Eliecer Gaitan]], Le\u00f3n de Greiff Auditorium (home of the Bogot\u00e1 Philharmonic Orchestra), and the Open Air Theater \"La Media Torta\", where musical events are also held.\n\nThe Ibero-American Theater Festival, is not the only acclaimed festival. There are many other regional and local theater festivals that are celebrated and maintain the city active year-round . Amongst these is the \"Alternative Theater Festival\".{{citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\nBogot\u00e1 has its own film festival, the [[Bogot\u00e1 Film Festival]], and many theaters, showing both contemporary films and art cinema. Bogota's international art fair, [[ArtBo]], takes place in October of every year and showcases thousands of works covering arts across all formats, movements, and concepts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thecitypaperbogota.com/culture/the-international-art-fair-of-bogota-ready-to-host-the-world/20815|title=The International Art Fair of Bogot\u00e1 ready to host the world|last=Staff|first=The City Paper|date=2018-10-17|website=The City Paper Bogot\u00e1|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-10}}</ref>\n\nThe main cultural center of the city is the La Candelaria, historic center of the city, with a concentration of universities and museums. In 2007 Bogot\u00e1 was designated the Ibero-American cultural Capital of Iberoamerica.\n\n=== Religion ===\nBefore the [[Spanish conquest of the Muisca|Spanish conquest]], the beliefs of the inhabitants of Bogot\u00e1 formed part of the [[Muisca religion]]. From the colonial period onwards, the city has been predominantly Roman Catholic. Proof of this religious tradition is the number of churches built in the historic city center. The city has been seat of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Bogot\u00e1]] since 22 March 1564. The seat of the Archbishop is the [[Primatial Cathedral of Bogot\u00e1]]; the archdiocese itself is located in new buildings in the north of the city. However a large group of the population nowadays declares itself non-practicing.{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n\nThe city has a mosque located in the area of Chapinero called the Estambul mosque,<ref>[http://mezquitaestambulbogota.es.tl/PORTADA-.htm Portada] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512211338/http://mezquitaestambulbogota.es.tl/PORTADA-.htm |date=12 May 2013 }}. Mezquita Estambul Bogota.</ref> a mosque being built on the Calle 80 with Cra 30 called Abou Bakr Alsiddiq mosque<ref>[http://mezquitabogota.org/index.html Casa | Mezquita Bogota, Islam en bogota] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202235319/http://mezquitabogota.org/index.html |date=2 December 2013 }}. Mezquitabogota.org.</ref> and which is the first in the city to have the traditional Islamic architecture, and an Islamic Center called Al-Qurtubi.<ref>[http://www.piensaislam.com/ Islam en Colombia, Bogota: Mezquita, Conferencias, Informaci\u00f3n] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130405031902/http://piensaislam.com/ |date=5 April 2013 }}. Piensaislam.com.</ref>\n\nThe main [[Ashkenazi]] Jewish synagogue (there are a total of 4 synagogues in Bogot\u00e1) is located on 94th street (also called State of Israel avenue).\n\nAn Eastern Orthodox church and the San Pablo Anglican Cathedral, the mother church of the Episcopal Church in Colombia, are both located in Chapinero. The [[Bogot\u00e1 Colombia Temple]] of [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] is located in the Niza neighborhood. There are four Buddhist centers located in the north of the city. There is also a wide variety of Protestant churches in different parts of the city, including the Bogot\u00e1 Baptist Chapel, the non-denominational Union Church, and the St. Matthaus Evangelical Lutheran Church which holds services in German as well as Spanish for the German-Colombian community.\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Torre central de la iglesia de Lourdes en Bogot\u00e1.JPG|Church of Our Lady of Lourdes\nFile:El Lugar de Su Presencia Exterior.png|[[Protestantism|Protestant]] [[Megachurch]] \nFile:Iglesia SUD en Bogot\u00e1.jpg|Bogot\u00e1 Colombia Mormon Temple\nFile:View from the local Transmilenio of the Abou Bakr Alsiddiq Mosque 2013.jpg|Abou Bakr Alsiddiq Mosque\n</gallery>\n\n=== Cuisine ===\nThere is a broad array of restaurants in Bogot\u00e1 that serve typical and international food. Parque de la 93, Usaqu\u00e9n, Zona T, The [[G Zone]], La Macarena, La Candelaria, The parkway and the International Center are some of the main sectors where a number of international restaurants are found, ranging from Argentinian, Peruvian, Venezuelan, Brazilian, Mexican, American establishments to Arabic, Asian, French, Italian, Russian and British bistros, rotisseries, steakhouses and pubs, just to name a few.\nTypical dishes of Bogot\u00e1 include the [[ajiaco]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://projects.washingtonpost.com/recipes/2006/03/01/ajiaco-bogotano-chicken-and-potato-soup/|title=Ajiaco Bogotano (Chicken and Potato Soup)|date=1 March 2006|work=Washington Post|access-date=21 February 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110101135832/http://projects.washingtonpost.com/recipes/2006/03/01/ajiaco-bogotano-chicken-and-potato-soup/|archive-date=1 January 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> a soup prepared with chicken, a variety of potatoes, corn on the cob, and ''[[Galinsoga parviflora|guascas]]'' (an herb), usually served with sour cream and capers, and accompanied by avocado and rice.\n\n[[Tamale]] is a very traditional Bogot\u00e1 dish. Colombian tamal is a paste made with rice, beef, pork and/or chicken (depending on the region), chickpea, carrot, and spices, wrapped in [[plantain (cooking)|plantain]] leaves and steam-cooked.\n\nFigs with [[arequipe]], strawberries with cream, ''postre de natas'' and ''cuajada con melao'' are some of the main desserts offered in the city. [[Canelazo]] is a hot drink from the Altiplano prepared with [[aguapanela]], cinnamon and [[aguardiente]]. Another hot beverage is the carajillo, made with coffee (tinto as it is known in Colombia) and aguardiente.\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Ajiaco.jpg|[[Ajiaco]] is one of the city's most representative dishes\nFile:Chocolate Especial.jpg|\"Chocolate santafere\u00f1o\" (Santafe hot chocolate), [[almoj\u00e1bana]], cheese and [[pandebono]]\n</gallery>\n\n=== Parks and recreation ===\nThere are numerous parks in Bogot\u00e1, many with facilities for concerts, plays, movies, storytellers and other activities.\n* [[Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar Metropolitan Park]] is a large park regularly used to stage free concerts (such as the annual [[Rock al Parque]] festival). <!--The whole complex is five times bigger than central park. Which central park? Maybe the area should be stated-->\n* The public [[National Park (Bogot\u00e1)|''Parque Nacional'' (National Park)]] has green spaces, ponds, games for children, foot and bicycle paths, and venues for entertainment such as public screenings of movies and concerts and events organized by the Council of Bogot\u00e1\n* The [[Bogot\u00e1 Botanical Garden]] (''Jard\u00edn Bot\u00e1nico de Bogot\u00e1'')\n* [[93 Park|Parque de la 93]] has day-time leisure activities and nightlife. Several of the top restaurants and bars in the city are in this park, the park is known around the world like the Colombian [[Pike Place]] by having the first [[Starbucks]] in all the country and [[Carl's Jr.]] as well.\n* Mundo Aventura is an [[amusement park]], with an entry charge and charges for the different attractions. It has rides for adults and children, a [[petting zoo]], and the \"cerdodromo\", where pigs race.\n* Salitre M\u00e1gico is another [[amusement park]] with rides and attractions. The park is near the Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar park, where concerts are held throughout the year.\n* Parque del Chic\u00f3 has trees, gardens, artificial creeks and ponds, and a colonial style house converted into a museum; [[Museo del Chic\u00f3]]\n* To the north of Bogot\u00e1, in the municipality of [[Tocancip\u00e1]]; [[Jaime Duque Park]] has rides, a giant map of Colombia, various exhibits, a zoo, and a big hand holding the world symbolizing God. There is a reproduction of the [[Taj Mahal]] in the park with a collection of reproductions of famous paintings. The park is also used for large concerts, mainly electronic music ones.\n* [[Maloka Museum|Maloka]] is an interactive museum of sciences\n* [[Bogot\u00e1 Savannah Railway|Tourist train]] is a sightseeing train, popular with Bogot\u00e1 residents, which runs to outlying towns [[Zipaquir\u00e1]], [[Cajic\u00e1]] and [[Nemoc\u00f3n]] along the lines of the former [[Bogot\u00e1 Savannah Railway]] on weekends. The route to Zipaquir\u00e1 (known for its [[Salt Cathedral of Zipaquir\u00e1|salt cathedral]]) is {{convert|53|km|0|abbr=off}} long. Another line goes towards the north for {{convert|47|km|0|abbr=on}} and ends at [[Brice\u00f1o, Boyac\u00e1|Brice\u00f1o]].\n* The [[Usaqu\u00e9n Park]] is another of the most important parks in the city several of the best restaurants in this city are located there, is recognized to have street performers such as storytellers, magicians, jugglers, etc. and also for being one of the most decorated parks in the city during Christmas time.\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Lago del Parque Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar.JPG|[[Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar Park]]\nFile:Parque de los periodistas (Bogot\u00e1).jpg|Journalists' park\nFile:Bogot\u00e1 Parque de la 93.JPG|93 Park\nFile:Parque Santander noche 2.JPG|Santander park\nFile:BOG El Virrey hacia la 15.JPG|El Virrey park\n</gallery>\n\n== Sports ==\n[[File:Bogot\u00e1 Estadio.JPG|thumb|[[Estadio El Camp\u00edn]]]]\n\nThe District Institute for Recreation and Sport promotes recreation, sports and use of the parks in Bogot\u00e1.\n\n[[Association football|Football]] has been declared a symbol of Bogot\u00e1, and is widely played in the city. There are three professional clubs in the city, [[Club Santa Fe|Santa Fe]], [[Millonarios F\u00fatbol Club|Millonarios]], and [[La Equidad]]. The main stadium in the city is The Camp\u00edn Stadium (Estadio Nemesio Camacho El Camp\u00edn) home of the local teams [[Club Santa Fe|Santa Fe]] and [[Millonarios]], In 2001 The Camp\u00edn Stadium has been the place for the [[2001 Copa Am\u00e9rica]] final between the [[Colombia|Colombia national football]] and the [[Mexico|Mexico national football]], final score 1\u20130 in favor of the home team and finally getting their first continental cup. The other soccer venue is the multi-use Techo Metropolitan Stadium which is the home of [[La Equidad]].\n\nOther major sporting venues are the covered Coliseum El Camp\u00edn, the Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar Aquatic Complex, the Sports Palace, the El Salitre Sports Venue which includes the [[Luis Carlos Gal\u00e1n Velodrome]] (which hosted the [[1995 UCI Track Cycling World Championships]]), the El Salitre Diamond Ballpark and the [[BMX]] track \"Mario Andr\u00e9s Soto\".\n\nBogot\u00e1 hosted the first Bolivarian Games held in 1938. The city hosted the National Games in 2004, winning the championship. It was a sub-venue Bolivarian Pan American Games. In addition, the city on the route of the Tour of Colombia.\n\nAfter being a major venue city for the [[2011 FIFA U-20 World Cup]] that was held in [[Colombia]], the Colombian Football Federation announced that Bogot\u00e1 will be one of the venue cities to host the [[2016 FIFA Futsal World Cup]] as well.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fcf.com.co/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4670:copa-mundial-de-futsal-de-la-fifa-se-jugara-en-colombia-en-2016&catid=4:&Itemid=296 |title=Copa Mundial de Futsal de la FIFA se jugar\u00e1 en Colombia en 2016 |publisher=fcf.com.co |date=28 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203012230/http://fcf.com.co/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4670%3Acopa-mundial-de-futsal-de-la-fifa-se-jugara-en-colombia-en-2016&catid=4%3A&Itemid=296 |archivedate=3 December 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n=== Sports teams ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Team\n! scope=\"col\" | League (Cup) / Sport\n! scope=\"col\" | Stadium / Coliseum\n! scope=\"col\" | Founded\n! scope=\"col\" | Championships\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[Independiente Santa Fe|Santa Fe]]\n| [[Categor\u00eda Primera A]] / Football\n| [[Estadio El Camp\u00edn|El Camp\u00edn Stadium]]\n| 1941\n| 16 (9 Primera A, 1 [[Copa Sudamericana]], 1 [[Suruga Bank Championship]], 2 [[Copa Colombia]], 3 [[Superliga Colombiana|Superliga]])\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[Millonarios F.C.|Millonarios]]\n| Categor\u00eda Primera A / Football\n| El Camp\u00edn Stadium\n| 1946\n| 20 (15 Primera A, 1 [[Copa Merconorte]], 3 Copa Colombia, 1 Superliga)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[La Equidad]]\n| Categor\u00eda Primera A / Football\n| [[Estadio Metropolitano de Techo|Metropolitano de Techo Stadium]]\n| 1982\n| 1 (1 Copa Colombia)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[Bogot\u00e1 F.C.]]\n| [[Categor\u00eda Primera B]] / Football\n| Metropolitano de Techo Stadium\n| 2003\n| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[Tigres F.C.]]\n| Categor\u00eda Primera B / Football\n| Metropolitano de Techo Stadium\n| 2016\n| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[Guerreros de Bogot\u00e1]]\n| [[Baloncesto Profesional Colombiano|Liga DirecTV]] / Basketball\n| El Salitre Coliseum\n| 2011\n| 1 (1 league)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[Piratas de Bogot\u00e1]]\n| Liga DirecTV / Basketball\n| El Salitre Coliseum\n| 1995\n| 4 (4 league)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[Bogota Bulldogs]]\n| [[Australian rules football]]\n| \n| 2015\n| \n|-\n|}\n\n== Symbols ==\nThe flag originated with the insurgency movement against the colonial authorities which began on 20 July 1810, during which the rebels wore armbands with yellow and red bands, as these colours were those of the [[Flag of Spain|Spanish flag]] used as the flag for the New Kingdom of Granada. {{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}\n\nOn 9 October 1952, exactly 142 years after these events, decree 555 of 1952 officially adopted the patriotic armband as the flag of Bogot\u00e1.<ref>{{cite web|year=2007 |url=http://www.bogotaturismo.gov.co/ciudad/simbolos/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20110707052924/http://www.bogotaturismo.gov.co/ciudad/simbolos/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 July 2011 |title=Simbolos de Bogot\u00e1 |publisher=Alcald\u00eda Mayor de Bogot\u00e1 |accessdate=29 December 2008 |language=Spanish }}</ref> The flag of Cundinamarca follows the same pattern, plus a light blue tile which represents the Virgin Mary's cape.\n\nThe flag itself is a yellow band above a red one. The yellow denotes the gold from the earth, as well as the virtues of justice, clemency, benevolence, the so-called \"mundane qualities\" (defined as nobility, excellence, richness, generosity, splendour, health, steadfastness, joy and prosperity), long life, eternity, power and constancy. The red denotes the virtue of charity, as well as the qualities of bravery, nobility, values, audacity, victory, honour and furor, Colombians call it the blood of their people. {{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}\n\nThe coat of arms of the city was granted by emperor [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V (Charles I of Spain)]] to the [[New Kingdom of Granada]], by royal decree given in [[Valladolid]], Spain on 3 December 1548. It contains a black eagle in the center, which symbolises steadfastness. The eagle is also a symbol of the Habsburgs, which was the ruling family of the Spanish empire at the time. The eagle is crowned with gold and holds a red pomegranate inside a golden background. The border contains olive branches with nine golden pomegranates on a blue background. The two red pomegranates symbolize audacity, and the nine golden ones represent the nine states which constituted the New Kingdom of Granada at the time. In 1932 the coat of arms was officially recognized and adopted as the symbol of Bogot\u00e1. {{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}\n\nBogot\u00e1's anthem lyrics were written by Pedro Medina Avenda\u00f1o; the melody was composed by Roberto Pineda Duque. The song was officially declared the anthem by decree 1000 31 July 1974, by then Mayor of Bogot\u00e1, An\u00edbal Fernandez de Soto.\n\n== International relations ==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in South America}}\n{{More citations needed section|date=April 2015}}\n\n=== Twin towns and sister cities ===\nBogot\u00e1 is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n\n* {{flagdeco|US}} [[New York City]], United States<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/ia/gp/html/partner/partner.shtml|title=New York City Global Partners|date=14 August 2013|accessdate=15 October 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130814165415/http://www.nyc.gov/html/ia/gp/html/partner/partner.shtml|archivedate=14 August 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* {{flagdeco|UK}} [[London]], United Kingdom<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=mD-gLI8TIz8C&lpg=PP1&pg=PT290#v=onepage|title=Top 10 of London: 250 lists about London that will simply amaze you!|first=Alexander|last=Ash|date=23 April 2012|publisher=Octopus|accessdate=15 October 2017|via=Google Books|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170910125536/https://books.google.nl/books?id=mD-gLI8TIz8C&lpg=PP1&pg=PT290#v=onepage|archive-date=10 September 2017|url-status=live|isbn=9780600624899}}</ref>\n* {{flagdeco|US}} [[Chicago]], United States (2009)<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Colombia Reports |url=https://colombiareports.com/chicago-and-bogota-become-sister-cities/ |title=Chicago and Bogot\u00e1 become sister cities |accessdate=2017-09-10 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170910085525/https://colombiareports.com/chicago-and-bogota-become-sister-cities/ |archivedate=10 September 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref>\n* {{flagdeco|LIB}} [[Beirut]], Lebanon\n* {{flagdeco|US}} [[Washington, D.C.]], United States{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n* {{flagdeco|KOR}} [[Seoul]], South Korea<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Seoul Metropolitan Government |url=http://english.seoul.go.kr/policy-information/international-exchange/sister-cities/ |title=Sister Cities |accessdate=2017-09-10 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170705231232/http://english.seoul.go.kr/policy-information/international-exchange/sister-cities/ |archivedate=5 July 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Iraq}} [[Baghdad]], [[Iraq]] <ref name=\"Baghdad\">{{cite web|url=http://www.beirut.gov.lb/MCMSTest/Menu-Pages/SisterCitiesEN.aspx?NRMODE=Published&NRORIGINALURL=%2fwww%2ebeirut%2egov%2elb%2fMCMSEN%2fTwinning%2bthe%2bCities%2f&NRNODEGUID=%7b18839037-0140-436E-A1AF-7F8F3693C3E6%7d&NRCACHEHINT=NoModifyGuest# |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080221055403/http://www.beirut.gov.lb/MCMSTest/Menu-Pages/SisterCitiesEN.aspx?NRMODE=Published&NRORIGINALURL=%2Fwww.beirut.gov.lb%2FMCMSEN%2FTwinning+the+Cities%2F&NRNODEGUID=%7B18839037-0140-436E-A1AF-7F8F3693C3E6%7D&NRCACHEHINT=NoModifyGuest%23 |archivedate=21 February 2008 |title=Twinning the Cities |publisher=City of Beirut |accessdate=13 January 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>.\n* {{flagdeco|UAE}} [[Dubai]], United Arab Emirates (2008){{citation needed|date=June 2015}}\n* {{flagdeco|US}} [[Miami]], United States (1971)<ref>{{cite web|publisher=City of Miami |url=http://www.ci.miami.fl.us/mic/pages/SisterCities/Bogota.asp |title=Sister Cities Program |accessdate=2017-09-10 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611133617/http://www.ci.miami.fl.us/mic/pages/SisterCities/Bogota.asp |archivedate=11 June 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref>\n* {{flagdeco|IRN}} [[Tehran]], Iran{{citation needed|date=June 2015}}\n* {{flagdeco|PAK}} [[Lahore]], Pakistan<ref name=Shayan>{{cite web|url=http://www.peela.pk/column4.html|title=Ground Realities 4|last1=Syed Shayan|date=February 2015|publisher=Akhbar Peela|access-date=23 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305094736/http://www.peela.pk/column4.html|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Union of Ibero-American Capital Cities ===\nBogot\u00e1 is part of the [[Union of Ibero-American Capital Cities]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.munimadrid.es/UnidadWeb/Contenidos/EspecialInformativo/RelacInternac/RRII/HermanamientosyAcuerdos/Files/hermanamiento_UCCI.pdf |title=Declaraci\u00f3n de Hermanamiento m\u00faltiple y solidario de todas las Capitales de Iberoam\u00e9rica (12-10-82) |date=12 October 1982 |accessdate=2015-03-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510114810/http://www.munimadrid.es/UnidadWeb/Contenidos/EspecialInformativo/RelacInternac/RRII/HermanamientosyAcuerdos/Files/hermanamiento_UCCI.pdf |archivedate=10 May 2013 }}</ref> from 12 October 1982 establishing brotherly relations with the following cities:\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* {{flagicon|AND}} [[Andorra la Vella]], Andorra\n* {{flagicon|PAR}} [[Asunci\u00f3n]], Paraguay\n* {{flagicon|ARG}} [[Buenos Aires]], Argentina\n* {{flagicon|VEN}} [[Caracas]], Venezuela\n* {{flagicon|GUA}} [[Guatemala City]], Guatemala\n* {{flagicon|CUB}} [[Havana]], Cuba\n* {{flagicon|BOL}} [[La Paz]], Bolivia\n* {{flagicon|PER}} [[Lima]], Peru\n* {{flagicon|POR}} [[Lisbon]], Portugal\n* {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Madrid]], Spain\n* {{flagicon|NCA}} [[Managua]], Nicaragua\n* {{flagicon|MEX}} [[Mexico City]], Mexico\n* {{flagicon|URU}} [[Montevideo]], Uruguay\n* {{flagicon|PAN}} [[Panama City]], Panama\n* {{flagicon|ECU}} [[Quito]], Ecuador\n* {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Brasilia]], Brazil\n* {{flagicon|CRC}} [[San Jose (Costa Rica)|San Jose]], Costa Rica\n* {{flagicon|USA}} {{flagicon|PUR}} [[San Juan (Puerto Rico)|San Juan]], Puerto Rico, United States \n* {{flagicon|SLV}} [[San Salvador]], El Salvador\n* {{flagicon|CHI}} [[Santiago]], Chile\n* {{flagicon|DOM}} [[Santo Domingo]], Dominican Republic\n* {{flagicon|HON}} [[Tegucigalpa]], Honduras\n{{Div col end}}\n\n=== Partnerships and cooperations ===\nOther forms of cooperation and city friendship similar to the twin city programmes exist:\n* {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Turin]], Italy<ref name=\"Turin twinnings\">{{cite web|url=http://www.comune.torino.it/relint/inglese/gemellaggieaccordi/index.shtml|title=International Affairs \u2013 Twinnings and Agreements|accessdate=2013-08-06|last=Pessotto|first=Lorenzo|work=International Affairs Service in cooperation with Servizio Telematico Pubblico|publisher=City of Torino|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618182559/http://www.comune.torino.it/relint/inglese/gemellaggieaccordi/index.shtml|archivedate=2013-06-18}}</ref>\n\n== Panoramas ==\n{{wide image|Panorama vanas bogotaf.jpg|1200px|align-cap=centre|Panoramic view of Bogot\u00e1}}\n{{wide image|PanoramaPlacaBolivarBogota.jpg|1200px|align-cap=centre|View of [[Bol\u00edvar Square]], Bogot\u00e1}}\n\n== Notable people ==\n{{Columns-list|\n* [[Arturo Acevedo Vallarino]] (1873\u20131950), director of silent films\n* [[Haider Ackermann]] (1971\u2013), fashion designer\n* [[Alberto Castilla]] (1883\u20131938), engineer, journalist, poet, writer, mathematician and musician\n* [[Guillermo Cano Isaza]] (1925\u20131986), journalist and editor of the ''[[El Espectador]]'' newspaper\n* [[Carolina G\u00f3mez]] Miss Universe 1994, first runner up, actress, presenter, model\n* [[Esteban Chaves]] (1990\u2013), professional bicycle road racer\n* [[Miguel Antonio Caro]] (1843\u20131909), politician and 1894\u20131898 President of Colombia\n* [[Fernando Cepeda Ulloa]] (1938\u2013), politician\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Vicente Concha]] (1867\u20131929), former president of Colombia\n* [[Esteban Cort\u00e1zar]] (1984\u2013), fashion designer\n* [[Rufino Jos\u00e9 Cuervo]] (1844\u20131911), writer, linguist and philologist\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Domingo Duquesne]] (1748\u20131822), theologist and [[List of Muisca scholars|Muisca scholar]]\n* [[Ana Luc\u00eda Dom\u00ednguez]] (1983\u2013), Colombian actress and model\n* [[Hernando Dur\u00e1n Duss\u00e1n]] (1920\u20131998), politician\n* [[Andrea Echeverri]] (1965\u2013), musician, lead singer of [[Aterciopelados]]\n* [[Pedro Franco]] (1991\u2013), footballer\n* [[Nancy Friedemann-S\u00e1nchez]], visual artist\n* [[Santiago Gamboa]] (1965\u2013), writer\n* [[Rodrigo Garc\u00eda (director)|Rodrigo Garc\u00eda]] (1959\u2013), film director, son of [[Gabriel Garc\u00eda M\u00e1rquez]]\n* [[\u00c1lvaro G\u00f3mez Hurtado]] (1919\u20131995), politician\n* [[Laureano G\u00f3mez]] (1889\u20131965), former president of Colombia\n* [[Miguel G\u00f3mez (photographer)|Miguel G\u00f3mez]] (1974\u2013), photographer\n* [[Ana Mar\u00eda Groot]] (1952\u2013), anthropologist and archaeologist\n* [[Juan B. Guti\u00e9rrez]], (1973\u2013), writer and mathematician\n* [[Rudolf Hommes Rodr\u00edguez]] (1943\u2013), politician\n* [[John Leguizamo]] (1964\u2013), actor and comedian\n* [[Alfonso L\u00f3pez Caballero]] (1944\u2013), politician\n* [[Albert