>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/20/coronavirus-coffee-prices-rise-as-countries-hoard-food-supplies-lifting-farmers.html|title=Farmers could be winners as coffee prices spike and countries hoard during the pandemic|last=Tan|first=Weizhen|date=April 19, 2020|website=CNBC|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> These coffeehouses play a prominent role in supporting [[Developing country|developing economies]] by waging a variety of [[coffee wars]] to gain market share.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://europe.businesschief.com/leadership/340/Top-10:-Global-Coffee-Shop-Chains|title=Top 10: Global Coffee Shop Chains|last=Burns|first=Sergio|date=December 14, 2014|website=europe.businesschief.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statista.com/statistics/270091/coffee-house-chains-ranked-by-revenue/|title=Coffeehouse chains: leader revenues 2015|last=|first=|date=|website=Statista|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Often these coffeehouse chains pay a [[Premium pricing|premium]] above market price in order to alleviate [[fair trade]] and [[Sustainable agriculture|sustainable farming]] concerns. Developing countries that participate in the coffee market wield considerate influence on [[Economics of coffee|global coffee economics]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Graaff|first=J. de|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Economics_of_Coffee.html?id=F_ITAQAAIAAJ|title=The Economics of Coffee|date=1986|publisher=Pudoc|isbn=978-90-220-0900-0|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Siddique|first=M. A. B.|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Economics_of_Tea_and_Coffee_Consumpt.html?id=3I7TAAAACAAJ|title=The Economics of Tea and Coffee Consumption in Australia|date=1990|publisher=Department of Economics, University of Western Australia|isbn=978-0-86422-622-8|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Main exporters by country in 2018 ==\nAccording to the World Atlas, the main [[Export|exporters]] of coffee beans as of 2019 are:<ref name=\":0\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n!Country\n!60 kilogram bags\n!Metric Tons\n!Pounds\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Coffee production in Brazil|Brazil]]\n| 44,200,000\n| 2,652,000\n| 5,714,381,000\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Vietnam}} [[Coffee production in Vietnam|Vietnam]]\n| 27,500,000\n| 1,650,000\n| 3,637,627,000\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Colombia}} [[Coffee production in Colombia|Colombia]]\n| 13,500,000\n| 810,000\n| 1,785,744,000\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Indonesia}} [[Coffee production in Indonesia|Indonesia]]\n| 11,000,000\n| 660,000\n| 1,455,050,000\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Ethiopia}} [[Coffee production in Ethiopia|Ethiopia]]\n| 6,400,000\n| 384,000\n| 846,575,000\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Honduras}} [[Coffee production in Honduras|Honduras]]\n| 5,800,000\n| 348,000\n| 767,208,000\n|-\n|{{flagicon|India}} [[Coffee production in India|India]]\n| 5,800,000\n| 348,000\n| 767,208,000\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Uganda}} [[Coffee production in Uganda|Uganda]]\n| 4,800,000\n| 288,000\n| 634,931,000\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Coffee production in Mexico|Mexico]]\n| 3,900,000\n| 234,000\n| 515,881,000\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Guatemala}} [[Coffee production in Guatemala|Guatemala]]\n| 3,400,000\n| 204,000\n| 449,743,000\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Peru}} [[Coffee production in Peru|Peru]]\n| 3,200,000\n| 192,000\n| 423,287,000\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Nicaragua}} [[Coffee production in Nicaragua|Nicaragua]]\n| 2,200,000\n| 132,000\n| 291,010,000\n|-\n|{{flagicon|China}} [[Coffee production in China|China]]<sup>(2013/14 est.)</sup><ref>[http://www.ico.org/documents/cy2014-15/icc-115-7e-study-china.pdf ICO - Coffee in China]</ref>\n| 1,947,000\n| 116,820\n| 257,544,000\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Ivory Coast}} [[Coffee production in Ivory Coast|Ivory Coast]]\n| 1,800,000\n| 108,000\n| 238,099,000\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Costa Rica}} [[Coffee production in Costa Rica|Costa Rica]]\n| 1,492,000\n| 89,520\n| 197,357,